<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT July 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI -- China's air transport industry will grow by an
average of 9.5 percent annually in the next 20 years, Boeing
Commercial Airplane Group predicted in its 1998 market outlook.
</P>
<P>
The forecast growth rate, the highest in the world, almost
doubles the global average figure in the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
Boeing has also predicted that China's airlines will add 1,800
new jetliners in 20 years, with the value of the increased
aircraft totaling 125 billion
U.S. dollars. (China-Boeing-Transport)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- The Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and
the United Nations Command (UNC) have agreed on the delivery of
the remains of the nine crewmen in a submarine who died in a
recent incident.
</P>
<P>
In a colonel-level meeting Thursday afternoon, the UNC and the
DPRK army set the handover for Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The remains will be returned to the DPRK army at the truce
village of Panmunjom by a UNC honor guard, a UNC spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The UNC and the DPRK army had agreed at general-level talks
Tuesday to discuss details of the return at the Thursday
meeting. (S.Korea-DPRK-Sub)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
GENEVA -- Six staff-members of the International Committee of
the Red Cross (ICRC), who have been missing for a week in eastern
Ethiopia, must have been abducted, said an ICRC official here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The six, five Ethiopian nationals of Somali origin and one
Swiss national, were seen walking with unidentified armed men,
ICRC spokesman Michael Kleiner was quoted by Reuters as
saying. (ICRC-Abduction-Ethiopia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG -- U.S. President Bill Clinton flew into Hong Kong,
the last stop of his China visit, Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
The special plane carrying the president and the first lady
from the scenic city of Guilin in southwest China landed at 20:35
local time (12:35 GMT) at the new Hong Kong International Airport,
which was officially opened by Chinese President Jiang Zemin at a
grand ceremony Thursday morning. (Hong Kong-Clinton-Arrival)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- The Royal Government will mobilize about 80,000
policemen to ensure the security of the coming elections,
Cambodian Second Prime Minister Hun Sen said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen, who is also vice president of the Cambodian People's
Party (CPP), made the remark during a meeting with Korishige
Anami, visiting Director-general of the Asian Affairs Bureau of
the Japanese Ministry of Foreign Affairs. (Cambodia-Hun
Sen-Electio)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's Foreign Minister Jawad Anani has said that
Jordanian-Israeli ties are almost at a standstill and both are at
the minimum level of contact and coordination, according to the
official Petra News Agency here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Official contacts between Jordan and Israel are currently
numbered. Most of the contacts are minimized in certain fields
such as water (sharing)," Anani told reporters Wednesday night
after meeting the European Union ambassadors to
Jordan. (Jordan-Israel) 
</P>
