<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Unveils Plans to Modernize NHS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair on
Thursday pledged to provide the National Health Service with the
resources it needs to modernize for the future.
</P>
<P>
Announcing a "crusade for excellence" at the NHS
Confederation's 50th anniversary meeting, Blair said the
government is to set up a modernization fund for the NHS in a bid
to tie extra funding to progress on waiting times and
accessibility.
</P>
<P>
Health economists say the NHS needs an extra eight billion
pounds (13.3 billion U.S. dollars) over the next three years just
to maintain its earlier rate of growth, which has been driven by
advances in medical technology.
</P>
<P>
Blair said he could not reveal the size of this 50th birthday
present just yet, but promised the NHS would get the resources it
needed.
</P>
<P>
"I want a health service with the confidence that its funding
will allow it to plan ahead, to be creative, to develop services,
in the knowledge that they will be there not just today but in the
years ahead," he said.
</P>
<P>
The new cash will be used to buy new technology, reduce waiting
lists, and pay for better training of staff.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
