<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Russian miners from across the nation have camped in Moscow
to protest the failure of the government to pay their salaries
over the past nine months. Sitting under big plastic sacks
installed before the White House, which is the seat of the
Russian administration, the minors also asked for the resignation
of President Boris Yeltsin and refused to descend into the mines
whose security conditions fall far short of the European norms.
</P>
<P>
-- In an interview with Liberation, Nigeria's Nobel Prize for
Liberature laureate Wole Soyinka asked the European Union to
maintain its sanctions against Nigeria, because he said the new
government is not cut from the regime of General Sani Abacha, who
died last month.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The CAC 40 stock index of the Paris Bourse has risen by 42
percent over the past six months. Some 14 billion francs (2.3
billion U.S. dollars) worth of stocks are traded each day over the
past six months in the Paris Bourse, as is compared with 9.5 billion
francs (1.6 billion U.S. dollars) in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
-- An old synagogue in Shanghai was re-opened on Wednesday as a
museum during the visit by U.S. President Bill Clinton to the city.
Rabbi Arthur Schneier of Manhattan presided over the ceremony in the
presence of U.S. first lady Hillary Clinton and her daugher Chelsea.
</P>
