<HEADLINE> Tax Evasion Serious in Malawi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NAIROBI, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Malawi only collected 3.6 billion
Kwacha (144 million Dollars) income tax in 1997/98 fiscal year as
against the targeted 3.8 billion Kwacha#,mainly due to tax
evasion, a Malawian tax official said.
</P>
<P>
Massive tax evasion and non-compliance are currently
frustrating efforts by Malawi's Income Tax Department to collect
income tax from individuals and companies to meet target,
Malawian Commissioner of Taxes, Clement Mononga, said at a press
briefing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Malawi News Agnecy quoted Mononga as saying: "We can't
give actual figures...but some people have registered businesses
for instance, minibus operarions, but are operating from their
homes, hence making it difficult for us to track them down."
</P>
<P>
In the 1996/97 period, only 3.5 billion Kwacha (140 millon
Dollars) was collected which was still lower than the target.
</P>
<P>
Mononga admitted that some individuals and businesses were
not paying tax out of ignorance but "others are deliberately
ignoring the department reminders and notices."
</P>
<P>
He accused some employers of deliberately not remitting tax
money deducted from their workers' wages and salaries.
</P>
<P>
He also attributed his department's underperformance to
understaffing and limited resources.
</P>
<P>
The government recently stopped departments and ministries
from recruiting staff in a bid to cut over-expenditure, which has
made many departments and ministries work on skeleton staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
