<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Sue France on Drinking Water Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission announced
its decision on Thursday to take legal action against France for
failure to combat pollution of surface water used for drinking
water.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union, will make an application to the European Court of Justice
against France.
</P>
<P>
The commission claimed that the untreated water of the rivers
used for abstraction of drinking water in Brittany, France, has
consistently registered nitrate levels of more than 50 milligrams
per litre of water.
</P>
<P>
The mandatory limit value of nitrates is 50 milligrams per
litre as set by the European council of ministers in the
Community's Surface Water Directive. The suggested limit value is
below 25 milligrams per litre.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials explained that the objective of the
community directive is to establish a minimum quality standard for
those untreated waters intended for the abstraction of drinking
water.
</P>
<P>
In Brittany, 80 percent of drinking water is taken from rivers
and reservoirs but in the last national survey for the period
between 1993 and 1995, 49 catchments in France exceeded the
community directive limit.
</P>
<P>
Forty-three of these catchments were located in Brittany, as a
result of intensive agricultural production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
