<HEADLINE> New Transit Route for Nepal to Boost Trade: Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The recent agreement by India to
open the Phulbari transit route leading to Bangladesh for all the
days of the week will boost Nepal's trade with Bangladesh and
other countries, the Nepali Ministry of Commerce said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Nepal in late May, Indian President K.R.
Narayanan formally announced that Nepal could use the transit
route for seven days a week, the ministry said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
Nepal received an official notification to that effect from the
Indian side on June 23, it said.
</P>
<P>
The transit route, which land-locked Nepal had been seeking as
an alternative to the Calcutta port in India since 1978, gives
Nepal an access to the Mongla port in Bangladesh through Phulbari
in northeastern India.
</P>
<P>
The route went into operation on September 1, 1997 on a
six-month trial basis, but had remained idle for most of the time
due to impractical operating modalities.
</P>
<P>
The business community in Nepal said the poor use was due to
the fact India allowed the route to be used only on Saturdays and
Sundays, as well as other obstacles like poor infrastructure in
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
In early March, India agreed to extend Nepal's use of the route
and agreed later that month to open it for four days a week after
commerce secretaries of the two countries met in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
When visiting Nepal in mid-March, Bangladeshi Finance Minister
Shah Kibria said his country was working to upgrade the physical
infrastructure to make the transit route economically viable in
the near future to boost trade between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
