<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR Advises Angolans in Namibia Not to Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commission for Refugees (UNHCR) is advising the Angolans in
Nambia not to return home following reports of renewed clashes
between warring factions in their country.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association Wednesday quoted UNHCR
assistant program officer Martha Mutilifa as saying that "due to
political unrest in Angola, the UNHCR feels that this is not the
right time to encourage voluntary repatriation".
</P>
<P>
In April, the UN agency launched a campaign to encourage
Angolans at Osire Refugee Camp of Namibia to return home as part
of a voluntary repatriation program.
</P>
<P>
However, fighting broke out at the weekend in Angola's Cuando
Cubango Province, which borders Nambia's Okavango region.
</P>
<P>
Mutilifa confirmed that asylum seekers were entering Nambia on
a daily basis from Angola, Congo, Burundi and Rwanda. Most of
them were Angolans. There were at Osire Camp 2186 refugees, and
2063 of them were Angolans, she said.
</P>
<P>
Namibian Broadcasting Corporation Television Wednesday quoted
the Angolan Ambassador to Namibia Garcia Bires as saying that the
National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) had taken
over two former UN bases in southeastern Angola and was expected
to take Calai soon.
</P>
<P>
A small number of government troops and UN peacekeepers have
fled into Namibia since the renewed fighting.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, new UN Security Council sanctions went into
force against the UNITA and its leader Jonas Savimbi for not
keeping to the Lusaka Peace Protocols, signed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The protocols provide for a UN-supervised peace settlement
between the Angolan government and the UNITA.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions include travel curbs and an oil and arms
embargo. The bank accounts of UNITA's leaders and their families
are frozen and the group may not trade in diamonds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
