<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Rejects Arafat's Criticism Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu rejected Thursday the condemnation issued by Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat of Israel's plan to expand the boundaries of
the disputed holy city of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after meeting here with visiting Canadian
Intergovernmental Affairs Minister Stephane Dion, Netanyahu urged
Arafat to stop what he called "incitement" on the Jerusalem which
threatens the security of Jews living in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said Israel can not accept the incitement and will
take measures to confront any actions that the Palestinians might
take in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's statement was in response to Arafat's speech
Wednesday that called on the Palestinian people to fight
Israel's Jerusalem expansion plan and protect the territorial
integrity of the holy city.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Palestinian Legislative Council in the West
Bank city of Ramallah, Arafat declared the battle for Jerusalem as
"one of life and death" and vowed that the Palestinians will not
surrender in the fight to get the city back to their hands.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no peace, no security and no stability in
Jerusalem without it being returned to the Palestinians," Arafat
told the session, which was also attended by members of the
Executive Committee of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
</P>
<P>
This was Arafat's sharpest reaction to Israeli Cabinet's
decision on June 21 to expand Jerusalem's boundaries to not only
incorporate some Jewish suburbs but also eight Jewish settlements
in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem, a city that is holy to Jews, Muslims and Christians,
is one of the most sensitive dispute in the Israeli-Palestinian
peace process. Israel took over the traditionally Arab East
Jerusalem in the 1967 Middle East War and late annexed it in 1980.
</P>
<P>
While Israel has declared the whole city as its eternal and
indivisible capital, the Palestinians want East Jerusalem to be
the capital of a future independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo accords, Jerusalem's status should be settled
through the permanent talks between the two sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
