<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> C'Wealth Optimistic About Abiola's Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of the
Commonwealth Emeka Anyaoku said here Thursday afternoon Nigeria's
most prominent opposition leader Moshood Abiola and other
political detainees will gain freedom soon.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very optimistic that before too long, Chief Abiola and
all the other political detainees will be released," Anyaoku said
at a press conference at the end of his four-day visit to the
west African country.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku's words confirmed reports which quoted his United
Nations counterpart Kofi Annan as saying earlier Thursday in
Abuja that the Nigerian government has promised
to release all political detainees.
</P>
<P>
Abiola, the presumed winner of the annulled June 12, 1993
presidential elections, is among the more than 200 political
prisoners and detainees across the country.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku, who is to leave for London later Thursday, said the
Commonwealth has long been asking for the release of Abiola and
part of his visit to Nigeria is to explore the possibility
for that to happen.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth chief disclosed that he had talked about that
question with both Abiola and the head of state, General
Abdulsalam Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
The conclusion of the imminent release of Abiola and other
political detainees came after these meetings.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has being suffering sanctions imposed by the
Commonwealth and other western countries for its alleged poor
human right situation and military dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
Since the sudden death of former military ruler General Sani
Abacha early June, the west has seen and been encouraged by
what Anyaoku called "positive developments" taking place in the
country.
</P>
<P>
These developments, characterized by the release of some 30
political detainees and the government's wide consultation for
national reconciliation, are expected to bring Nigeria back to
democracy, according to political analysts.
</P>
<P>
The release of Abiola is regarded as a key step toward true
national reconciliation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
