<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts: UN Environment, Housing Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The Task Force recommends that the United Nations Environment
Programme (UNEP) and the United Nations Center for Human
Settlements (HABITAT) examine, together with representatives of
business, industry and other economic interests, ways of involving
that community constructively in their deliberations." according
to the Task Force report.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation is made in view of the fact that
environment and human settlements policy must be more integrated
with economic decision-making. "This means that there must be a
well-balanced and effective continuing dialogue with business,
industry and other economic interests," the report noted.
</P>
<P>
The report also called for developing the Earthwatch system
for assessing the condition of the global environment.
Monitoring and assessment are closely linked to predicting
possible environmental emergencies which could threaten
security.
</P>
<P>
The Task Force recommended that UNEP and HABITAT maximize
their ability to provide early warning of possible environmental
and human settlement emergencies.
</P>
<P>
The Task Force designed its recommendations to address the
problems of institutional fragmentation and the lack of policy
coherence which were hampering the work of the United Nations in
the area of the environment and human settlements.
</P>
<P>
It called for the establishment of an inter-agency environment
management group to take a problem-solving, results-oriented
approach to joint action.
</P>
<P>
The Task Force emphasized the importance of strengthening the
United Nations presence in Nairobi, and stressed the need to
make the status of the United Nations office there commensurate
with other major U.N. centers, such as those at Vienna and Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The Task Force is made up of ministers, senior government
officials, senior United Nations officials and NGO
representatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Moves to Normalize Ties With Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has expressed readiness to
increase trade and economic cooperation with Syria in an effort to
normalize the bilateral relations severed in 1980, informed
sources said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi overture was made to Syrian officials by Iraqi Trade
Minister Mohammed Mehdi Saleh, who is on a visit here to discuss
ways of promoting bilateral cooperation in the fields of trade,
industry and health.
</P>
<P>
Iraq agreed to grant Syrian goods preferential treatment and
facilitate the launching of trade ventures and cooperation among
businessmen of the two countries, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Saleh has held talks with Syrian Health Minister Mohammed Iyad
Shatti, Minister of Economy and Trade Mohammed al-Imadi and
Chairman of the Syrian Chamber of Commerce Rateb Al-Shallah.
</P>
<P>
Saleh's visit is viewed as part of Iraq's efforts to normalize
its relations with Syria, which were severed in 1980 due to
Syria's support for Iran in the 1980-88 Iraq-Iran war.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have probed the possibility for Iraq to import
goods via Syria's Mediterranean ports and resume export of oil
through Syrian pipelines.
</P>
<P>
Under the oil-for-food program signed between Iraq and the
United Nations in 1996, Syria's pharmaceutical firms have taken
part in 12 tenders offered by Iraq to buy medicine. Syria was
awarded contracts worth 10 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The program, an exception of U.N. economic sanctions imposed on
Iraq after its invasion of Kuwait in 1990, allows Iraq to sell a
limited amount of oil to buy food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
Syria so far has signed with Iraq 20 million dollars worth of
contracts on exporting goods to Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
