<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Official Calls for Promoting ASEM Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A senior Singapore official
Thursday called for further strengthening of the ASEM (Asia-Europe
Meeting) process to promote cooperation between the two continents
and help Asia out of its present economic woes.
</P>
<P>
In a speech made at a dinner here in honor of the members of
the 2nd ASEM Vision Group Meeting, Singapore Minister for Law and
Foreign Affairs S. Jayakumar said the group has an important role
to play in the ASEM process and its recommendations will help
decide whether the ASEM process retains its momentum or lose its
direction.
</P>
<P>
The Vision Group, which was launched at the Second ASEM Summit
in London in April 1998, consists of members respectively
appointed by the 25 ASEM member countries and the European
Commission. It has been entrusted to formulate medium- to
long-term visions for enhanced Asia-Europe cooperation with
specific and "actionable" recommendations for the ASEM leaders.
</P>
<P>
"The challenge is to come up with new and bold initiatives
which government officials dealing with ASEM may hesitate to
propose, ideals which will have to be both practical and
pragmatic," Jayakumar said.
</P>
<P>
"Not being directly involved in ASEM's organization or
activities, the Vision Group will be able to objectively evaluate
ASEM's record and to recommend both medium and long-term
strategies for ASEM's future development," he added.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the situation in Asia, Jayakumar said: "The Asia
today bears little resemblance to the Asia that hosted ASEM I (in
1996)," adding that Asia has been in the grip of a severe economic
and financial crisis and Asia's economic woes will persist for the
short to medium term.
</P>
<P>
Touching on the cooperation between Asia and Europe during the
period between the first and second ASEM summits, the minister
said: "There were concerns that a Europe which is preoccupied with
its own integration and the onset of the Euro, will simply turn
its back on Asia at its time of need."
</P>
<P>
"Others questioned Europe's commitment to helping Asia manage
and overcome its problems," he added.
</P>
<P>
At the second ASEM summit, Europe demonstrated its continued
commitment to Asia by expressing its confidence and willingness to
help Asia deal with the crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
The ASEM Vision Group is on a two-day meeting here and has
formed three working groups to facilitate in-depth discussions on
three major areas of cooperation: "Man &AMP; Society", "Global Market"
and "Governance." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
