<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Meets Trade Union Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Thursday Held talks with leaders of the Zimbabwe Congress of
Trade Union (ZCTU) on issues affecting workers and the
macro-economic situation.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, the ZCTU held two nationwide strikes,
protesting high prices and demanding the government to remove the
2.5 percent sales tax.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, President of the ZCTU, Gibson Sibanda
told a press conference that their meeting with Mugabe has been
a ''major break through".
</P>
<P>
Sibanda said that the president, after listening to ZCTU's
grievances, sympathised with the workers' plight.
</P>
<P>
He said that they had a positive exchange of views with
Mugabe. This is an indication the government will listen to
workers' concerns, he added.
</P>
<P>
The ZCTU presented Mugabe with a position paper outlining the
workers demands which included the need for the government to
ensure the cost of basic goods will not continue to escalate.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is facing an economic crisis triggered by the crash
of the Zimbabwean Dollar against major currencies last year which
led to nationwide job stayaways.
</P>
<P>
Sibanda said, ''The dialogue that we opened today was long
overdue. These stayaways could have been avoided.''
</P>
<P>
He said that the ZCTU will consider what it will now do after
receiving government's response in two weeks. "We are confident
positive things will come out of these meetings," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Minister for Public Service, Labour and Social
Welfare, Florence Chitauro, Mugabe will table the ZCTU paper for
cabinet discussion next Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
