<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Calls for Fighting Extremism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Thursday urged the Islamic world to fight against extremist
activities.
</P>
<P>
"The Islamic countries should decisively face up to anyone
threatening the future of the Islamic nation and impede its
march," Mubarak told the opening ceremony of the tenth conference
of the Supreme Council for Islamic Affairs.
</P>
<P>
In an address read out by Egyptian Minister of Religious
Endowment Mahmoud Hamdi Zaqzouq, Mubarak stressed the urgent need
for confronting violence and terrorism inspired by extremists.
</P>
<P>
"These acts drain the potentials of the nation and divert it
from facing up to plots concocted by its enemies," he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 ministers of religious endowments and more than 1,000
delegates from 75 Islamic countries attended the four-day
conference aimed at forging a strategy to solidify the Islamic
society and brace up for challenges of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
"Should the Islamic world lag behind the modern age, it will be
left in backwardness and consigned to oblivion," he warned, adding
that Islamic home must be reorganized from within.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president stressed that real strength does not
rest on armaments, but the power of science, planning and the
possession of the most advanced inventions.
</P>
<P>
"The divided Islamic world of today undermines its own
capabilities and determination and paralyzes its activities, at a
time other blocs group themselves into one strong bloc," Mubarak
said, citing the European Union as a good example.
</P>
<P>
"It is a must for the Islamic world to strictly eliminate
everything that stands on the road of its modernization and to
challenge the terrorism and violence schemed by the radical
enemies of Islam," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
