<HEADLINE> Mozambique Elections Claimed to Be Peaceful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique's National Election
Committee (NEC) announced that the local elections held on June
30 in the country's 33 towns and cities were "peaceful".
</P>
<P>
The NEC statement said that though some separate incidents
happened, the elections proceeded peacefully " with no violence
and unrest", the Mozambican News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the polling stations started receiving voters at six
in the morning, though there were some delays for one reason or
another, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
But About 80 percent of voters did not turn up to cast their
votes in some areas.
</P>
<P>
The opposition National Resistance Movement (Renamo) Chairman
Afonso Dhlakama said that he was satisfied with the low turn-out
for the elections, saying it is a result of the boycott of the
elections by the Renamo and 11 other parties.
</P>
<P>
Dhlakama also called the president of the country to annul the
elections.
</P>
<P>
But NEC Chairman Leonardo Simbine said the right whether to
declare the election effective or not, is up for the Supreme
Court to decide.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the 33 towns and cities, with 1.9 million
voters, are expected to have their new mayors in 14 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
