<HEADLINE> Israel Accuses Syria of Supporting Hezbollah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Following an attack on Israeli
troops in south Lebanon Thursday, Israel renewed its accusation
against Syria for supporting the anti-Israel Hezbollah guerrilla
forces.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon as
saying that Syria is behind the attacks carried out by the Shiite
Muslim militant group Hezbollah, or Party of God.
</P>
<P>
Sharon, the leading hawk within the Israeli government, accused
Damascus of using Hezbollah as a bargain chip to obtain political
concessions from Israel.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the situation in south Lebanon should not
continue. But he fell short of elaborating on what steps Israel
will take to end the situation.
</P>
<P>
In the early morning of Thursday, Hezbollah fired rockets and
mortars to posts of Israeli troops in the western and central
sectors of the "security zone" in south Lebanon, wounding two
Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Israel has created the 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in
south Lebanon since 1985 after it withdrew the bulk of its troops
which invaded Lebanon in 1982. The invasion against Lebanon was
ordered by Sharon, then defense minister.
</P>
<P>
In last April, Israel offered to withdraw troops from south
Lebanon on condition that Lebanon agrees to guarantee the safety
of its northern border.
</P>
<P>
But Lebanese government, backed by its powerful ally Syria, has
rejected the offer and demanded Israel leave its territory
unconditionally. Israel held Syria responsible for the Lebanese
stand, saying Damascus is using the Lebanese issue as a bargain
chip to press Israel to return the Golan Heights that it has
seized from Syria in 1967. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
