<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> C'Wealth Ready to Help Nigeria: Anyaoku </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of the
Commonwealth Emeka Anyaoku said here Thursday afternoon that the
organization is ready to assist Nigeria for achieving a genuine
transition to democracy.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is at a crossroads and the historic opportunity now
available should not be missed, Anyaoku said at a press
conference before winding up his four-day visit to the west
African country.
</P>
<P>
It is clear the historic opportunity came with the sudden
death of former head of state, General Sani Abacha on June 8.
</P>
<P>
New leader General Abdulsalam Abubakar has ordered the release
of about 30 political detainees and held wide consultation with
various interest groups in the country about the future of the
nation.
</P>
<P>
What Abubakar has done have won widely welcome both at home
and abroad because they are taken as steps toward establishing "a
credible democracy and a strong and united Nigeria," said
Anyaoku.
</P>
<P>
The primary purpose of Anyaoku's visit is to hold discussions
with Abubakar and the two had three "good meetings" in the past
four days.
</P>
<P>
"I would expect that the new head of state of Nigeria will
before too long make a pronouncement on what the planned
transition for the country will be," Anyaoku told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"We should await that announcement," said Anyaoku, who is from
Nigeria himself.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever plan the head of state announces should be a plan
that meets the general will of Nigerians," he said, adding that
Nigerians are all sick of military rules and want to see the
military quickly back to barracks.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that it is ultimately for the Nigerians and
Nigerians alone to determine their own destiny.
</P>
<P>
But he said the Commonwealth and Nigeria's many friends in the
international community remain ready to offer their solidarity
and support, as well as any assistance Nigeria may require.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku said the 53-nation Commonwealth will be happy to help
Nigeria establish a new democratic order based on the experience
and expertise it has built up in facilitating and consolidating
transitions to multi-party democracy from military or one-party
rule in many other countries of the association.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth suspended the membership of Nigeria three
years ago when the Abacha administration hanged Ken Saro-Wiwa and
eight Ogoni minority activists in defiance of international calls
for mercy.
</P>
<P>
Now at the historic time, Anyaoku said, "Nigeria will return
to full membership of the Commonwealth when it becomes a
democracy."
</P>
<P>
According to him, Abubakar has assured him that although
Nigeria believed it had been unfairly treated by the
Commonwealth, he wanted to look to the future and not the past.
</P>
<P>
At the end of his visit, Anyaoku said, he will give Nigerians
a message of hope that the new administration is aware of what
needs to be done to restore genuine national reconciliation, the
dignity and self-respect of Nigerians, the sense of national
security and Nigeria's place in the international community.
</P>
