<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government-Gazprom Conflict Gone in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The conflict between the Russian
government and gas giant Gazprom has been resolved "within hours"
on Thursday after Vice-Premier Boris Nemtsov made a mediation,
according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov had a telephone conversation with Gazprom chief Rem
Vyakhirev who is visiting Vienna to mark the 30th anniversary of
Russian natural gas supplies to Austria.
</P>
<P>
The government will not annul its trust agreement on the
management of its 35-percent stake in Gazprom as the gas company
committed itself to regular payment of taxes and other deductions
towards the federal budget, Nemtsov said.
</P>
<P>
Gazprom will make all due payments to the federal budget fully,
and in return, the federal budget will clear its commitments on
gas consumption by government-financed organizations arising from
July 1, Nemtsov was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said all debts accumulated by Gazprom before July 1, which
total from 12 billion to 13 billion rubles (about 2 billion U.S.
dollars), will be checked by a special task force for settling
reciprocal debts.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko ordered
Nemtsov to abolish the trust agreement with Gazprom for its
shortage of tax payment and intended to convene an extraordinary
meeting of Gazprom shareholders.
</P>
<P>
Gazprom will pay the budget 4 billion rubles (some 645 million
U.S. dollars) each month, while the government will also have to
pay a considerable sum for gas, the deputy premier said.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin Thursday had telephone
conversations with Kiriyenko and presidential deputy chief of
staff Alexander Livshits on the Gazprom issue.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that he found right the government's raising the
question of more role of the state in managing this "large and
system-forming Russian company which is a national wealth." But,
he noted the country needs the Gazprom gas monopoly to remain
strong. "
</P>
<P>
Gazprom - a gas giant of Russia - is consolidating 60 main
industrial regions of Russia and plays an extremely important role
in the national economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
