<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Burns 51 Tonnes of Drugs (Updated) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 2 (Xinhua) -- In a move to show its determination
to fight drugs, Iran on Thursday burned 50 tonnes of opium and one
ton of heroin at a ceremony in northern Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was held to mark the occasion of the world
Anti-drug Day. Attending the ceremony were Iranian President
Mohammad Khatami, Prosecutor General Morteza Moghtadai, United
Nations Drug Control and Production (UNCDP) chief Pino Arlachi and
some foreign diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Over 2,000 young people cheered loudly when three archers shot
three burning arrows to the huge pile of drugs, which were worth
more than 800 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Khatami pledged to continue the
country's anti-drug fight, saying "as long as illegal drug
production exists in the world, we will continue our struggle
against drugs."
</P>
<P>
"We will fight all out against drug trafficking in the
country as we did during the past 20 years," he said, "and
we will encourage any cooperation with the UNCDP to control
and eliminate narcotics."
</P>
<P>
Head of Iran's anti-drug mission Mohammad Fallah said Iran has
allocated some 560 million dollars to install barriers along its
borders with Afghanistan and deployed 30,000 forces to prevent
drug smuggling through its eastern borders.
</P>
<P>
Fallah said that during the past two decades, Iran has lost
2,500 soldiers in armed clashes with drug traffickers, 97 of whom
died in the past Iranian year which ended on March 20.
</P>
<P>
Iran seized 195 tonnes of various narcotics in 1997 or 198
tonnes in the past Iranian year. But drug trafficking remains a
serious challenge because drug production in Afghanistan is
increasing and Iran is the shortest and cheapest transit road for
smuggling drugs to the European countries.
</P>
<P>
Praising Iran's important role in the anti-drug campaign,
Arlachi called on the international community to help Iran
continue its anti-drug fight because it neighbors Afghanistan, one
of the world biggest drug producing center.
</P>
<P>
To further UNCDP's cooperation with Iran, Arlachi said his
organization has decided to open an office in Tehran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
