<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Official Calls for Rushing Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 2 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.N. official on Thursday
stressed the need to speed up the delivery of spare parts to
Iraq's oil sector.
</P>
<P>
Benon Sevan, executive director of U.N. Iraq Program, told a
press conference that even if these spare parts would arrive in
Iraq in a short period of time, Iraq still could not export the
amount of oil that it is allowed under the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
He said that the drastic drop of oil prices on the world
markets was another reason to Iraq's possible failure to meet the
quota.
</P>
<P>
Under the fourth phase of the oil-for-food program, Iraq is
allowed to export 5.2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil to buy
food, medicine and other daily necessities for its people. But
Iraq has said time and again that it could not pump more than 4
billion dollars of oil due to the lack of spare parts in its oil
sector and the drop of oil prices on the world markets.
</P>
<P>
He complained that though spare parts were crucial to the
increase of Iraq's oil export and that he had reported to the
U.N. secretary-general in a bid to speed up the approval of
allocating 300 million U.S. dollars for Iraq's oil sector, it
still took the Security Council 63 days to finish the process of
the approval.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the U.N. secretary-general and U.N. Iraq
Program are committed to their obligations towards Iraq and that
the Security Council and the U.N. Sanctions Committee were
responsible for the delay of the approval.
</P>
<P>
He added that Iraq has signed 40 contracts with international
firms to purchase oil spare parts, but the U.N. Sanctions
Committee approved two of them up to now.
</P>
<P>
Sevan praised the cooperation of the Iraqi officials, and said
that the two sides have agreed to hold more talks when necessary.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, Sevan met with Iraqi Vice President Taha
Yassin Ramadan to discuss the ways to improve the implementation
of the oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Ramadan criticized U.S. representatives in
the U.N. Sanctions Committee for delaying and suspending hundreds
of oil-for-food contracts unjustifiably "in order to further
aggravate the Iraqi people's suffering and expose them to death."
</P>
<P>
Sevan, on his part, expressed his dissatisfaction with the
slow implementation of the oil-for-food contracts, saying he would
exert utmost efforts to speed up the implementation of these
contracts.
</P>
<P>
He also promised that the U.N. secretary-general would follow
up this issue to help accomplish them as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
