<HEADLINE> Palestinian Legislators to Visit U.S. Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Legislative Council
(PLC) Speaker Abu Ala (Ahmed Queria) Thursday called "a positive
step" the invitation from U.S. House Speaker Newt Gingrich asking
PLC members to visit the U.S. congress.
</P>
<P>
Ala will head a 10-member PLC delegation on its first visit to
the Capitol Hill later this month, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted as describing the invitation as "a positive step
towards the opening of dialog" between the PLC and the
U.S. Congress, which he said was "very pro-Israel."
</P>
<P>
The coming visit was mainly a result of the meeting between
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat and
Gingrich, which was held in Ramallah later May and hailed by both
sides as "positive." PNA officials said the meeting had created "a
real dialog" between the Palestinians and the Congress for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
During that talks, Gingrich suggested exchange of visits
between Palestinian and U.S. legislators.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have been at odds with the Congress over what
they call its pro-Israel stand, especially its position on the
status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Congress passed a bill three years ago mandating the
U.S. embassy in Tel Aviv to be moved to Jerusalem by May 31, 1999,
which would amount to a recognition of Israel's claim to the holy
city.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Israel in May, Gingrich outraged the
Palestinians by openly claiming that Jerusalem, whose status will
be determined in the final status talks, should remain the "united
and eternal capital of Israel." 
</P>
</TEXT>
