<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-02 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Visits Cyprus for Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary General
Kofi Annan's Special Advisor for Cyprus Diego Cordovez arrived
here Thursday for talks on resuming the peace process of the
Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Cordovez is expected to hold separate
meetings with Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the visit, Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides described it as "useful," but he said "we are not
anticipating any significant outcome."
</P>
<P>
United States Ambassador to Cyprus Kenneth Brill expressed
hope that Cordovez's visit will be "productive" and "help the
process move toward direct negotiations."
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between the Greek Cypriots and the Turkish
Cypriots broke down last summer when Denktash refused to continue
the process to protest against European Union's decision to start
accession talks with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Denktash says he will not return to the talks unless his
breakaway entity in northern Cyprus is internationally recognized
and Cyprus' efforts to win EU membership is suspended.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez's visit followed the adoption of two resolutions on
Cyprus by the U.N. Security Council early this week. The
resolutions call on the leaders of Cyprus' two communities to
"resume the direct dialog without further delay."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island to protect
the Turkish Cypriot minorities after a failed coup by the Greek
Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 the breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by Ankara against the
internationally recognized Republic of Cyprus dominated by the
Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying to reunify the island in a bizonal and
bicommunal formula, but so far no tangible results have been
achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
