<HEADLINE> Annan to Send Fact-Finding Mission to Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan has set up a panel of eminent persons on a fact-finding
mission to Algeria, his spokesman announced here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of this mission will be to gather information on
the situation in Algeria and present a report to him, which he
will make public," the spokesman Juan Carlos Brandt said.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian Government which invited Annan to do so, will
ensure "free and complete access to all sources of information
necessary for the panel to exercise its functions in order to have
a clear vision and a precise perception of the reality of the
situation in all its dimensions in Algeria today", he said.
</P>
<P>
An internal conflict, involving an Islamic movement, has hit
the country since 1992, with casualties numbering between 65,000
and 75,000 by Western accounts.
</P>
<P>
Headed by former Portuguese President Mario Soares, the panel
includes former Indian Prime Minister I.K. Gujral, former
Jordanian Prime Minister Abdel Karim Kabariti, former American
U.N. Permanent Representative Donald McHenry, former French
Secretary of State Simone Veil and Kenyan Attorney-General Amos
Wako.
</P>
<P>
The panel will go to Algeria as soon as arrangements are made
for it to start work, Brandt said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
