<HEADLINE> Bank in Uganda Addresses Millennium Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Standard Chartered Bank in Uganda
has begun to address the millennium issue which has been vexing
computer programmers for a long time.
</P>
<P>
Washington Matseira, the bank's managing director, called on
all people concerned to solve the problem and acknowledged that
his bank would be on top of the situation by the year 1999.
</P>
<P>
The bank will work closely with its customers and
non-customers to share information in this aspect, he added.
</P>
<P>
In their presentation at a function here Wednesday, Mark
Waller and Ian Weavers of the London-based Standard Chartered
Bank attributed the millennium problem to the failure by
programmers to consider the subsequent need to recognize the year
as belonging to 20 hundreds instead of 19 hundreds.
</P>
<P>
They said the millennium issue is so serious a problem that
fatal economic damage could be brought about to businesses of all
sizes and disciplines if not properly handled. 
