<HEADLINE> Russia Denies Sanctions against Latvia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry
Thursday denied the allegation from Latvia that it is taking
economic sanctions against the Baltic country, the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman for the foreign ministry Vladimir Rakhmanin told a
briefing that Russia is not applying any economic sanctions
against Latvia.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government cancelled discounts on international
carriage of most freight going to Latvia from the beginning of
July. It seems for the Baltic state to be an economic sanction
against Latvia.
</P>
<P>
Rakhmanin, however, said the measures were taken "in order to
streamline trade and economic relations with Latvia" and should
not be regarded as sanctions.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Latvian Foreign Minister Valdis Birkavs said that
Riga is preparing to launch a campaign to notify international
financial organization about Russia's economic pressure on Latvia.
</P>
<P>
Birkavs said that Russia is violating the principles and rules
of the International Monetary Fund and other international
financial organizations and is violating the joint communique of
the Group of Eight energy ministers on free transit of goods.
</P>
<P>
He noted despite Russia's statements on the need to protect its
national economic interests, many measures are aimed precisely
against Latvia. "This is especially evident in trade, the banking
sector, the energy sector, freight transit and road carriage,"
Birkavs said.
</P>
<P>
The Latvian official warned that Riga will inform the IMF, the
World Bank, the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development
and the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development
about the development of the situation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
