<HEADLINE> Palestinian Legislature Denounces Israel's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian Legislative
Council (PLC) issued a statement in the West Bank city Ramallah
Thursday, strongly denouncing Israel's plan to strengthen its hold
on the disputed holy city Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israel's decision to expand the boundaries of Jerusalem is
"illegal and discriminatory and is in violation of international
law and resolutions of the United Nations," the East
Jerusalem-based Palestinian news service the Jerusalem Media and
Communication Center quoted the PLC statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
The PLC stressed that East Jerusalem is occupied Palestinian
territory according to United Nations Security Council
resolutions 242 and 338, and the Palestinian side can not accept
any unilateral expansion of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The statement called on the United States, as a sponsor of the
Middle East peace process and an ally of Israel, to take a firm
and just position on the Arab-Israel conflict in general, and the
issue of Jerusalem in particular.
</P>
<P>
The PLC also reaffirmed its support to Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat's call for holding an urgent Arab summit as well as
a conference of foreign ministers of Islamic countries to address
the issue of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
It also urged the Security Council to adopt a resolution
denouncing the Jerusalem expansion plan.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the PLC special session in Ramallah on Wednesday,
Arafat already condemned the Israeli expansion plan and called on
the Palestinian people to fight to the end to protect the
territorial integrity of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
urged Arafat to stop incitement that could threaten the security
of Jewish residents in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem is one of the most sensitive issue in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process. Israel has occupied the
traditionally Arab East Jerusalem since 1967 and declared it as
its eternal capital, but the Palestinians want East Jerusalem to
be the capital of a future state.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo Accords, Jerusalem's status should be settled
through the Israeli-Palestinian permanent talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
