<HEADLINE> U.N. to Hold High-Level Discussion on World Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Economic
and Social Council (ECOSOC) will hold a session next week on world
trade, featuring the impact of the Asian economic crisis, ECOSOC
announced here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Not only investment flows but international trade patterns
are in a period of volatility following the 1997-98 East Asian
shock wave, conference sponsors said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, scheduled for July 6-8, takes place when growth in
dollar value of world exports is forecast to fall to roughly 2.5
percent in 1998 compared with 2.7 percent in 1997 and 4.3
percent in 1996, according to a U.N. survey.
</P>
<P>
A rapid drop in East Asian demand is reducing exports of
industrialized and developing countries, while East Asian exports
are hampered by a lack of financing.
</P>
<P>
The crisis has pulled down commodity prices and renewed fears
of protectionism in the industrialized markets at a time when
emerging markets are struggling to maintain financial stability in
large part through strong exports, ECOSOC noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
