<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increased UN Presence Called for in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Three west African leaders have
jointly called for an increased United Nations presence in Sierra
Leone to complement the sub-regional efforts at promoting peace
and security in that country.
</P>
<P>
The call was made at a mini-ECOWAS (Economic Community of West
African States) forum chaired by Nigeria's new leader General
Abdulsalam Abubakar, with visiting United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan in attendance.
</P>
<P>
President Charles Taylor of Liberia and President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah of Sierra Leone attended the meeting in the Nigerian
capital Abuja, which addressed a number of regional and
sub-regional issues.
</P>
<P>
A six-point communique issued Thursday and signed by the three
leaders and Annan, stated that the meeting discussed the need for
improved security and cooperation between Liberia and Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, held Wednesday, also considered "what
confidence-building measures could be introduced by the two
countries and how the UN and ECOWAS could assist."
</P>
<P>
Liberia has been accused of supporting Sierra Leone's ousted
junta and allied rebels in their fighting against Kabbah's
government and the west African peacekeeping force known as
ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
The communique stated that in the presence of the ECOWAS
chairman and Annan, the heads of state of Liberia and Sierra
Leone reached agreement on seven thorny issues affecting their
two countries, and pledged their support for the deployment of UN
and ECOMOG observers along their borders.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also condemned the continued rebel activities in
Sierra Leone as well as the "horrendous atrocities" that have
been committed.
</P>
<P>
They expressed their determination to cooperate and promote an
end to the fighting in Sierra Leone and foster peace and security
in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the remnants of the ousted junta and
allied rebels have launched a violent campaign against the
civilian population in the eastern and northern parts of the
country, perpetrating killing and maiming by chopping of people's
hands and legs.
</P>
<P>
The communique also said that both Taylor and Kabbah had
reaffirmed their commitment not to allow their territories to be
used for actions aimed at destabilizing the other, drawing
attention to the need to control the activities and movements of
demobilized former combatants.
</P>
<P>
It stated that both Taylor and Kabbah have agreed to check the
involvement of their citizens in destabilizing activities, and
urged the two leaders to commit those involved in such subversive
activities to prosecution.
</P>
<P>
The communique also expressed "grave concern" over the
situation in Guinea Bissau, and noted the on-going consultations
among ECOWAS member states on this matter.
</P>
<P>
It also commended the initiative by the Nigerian leader and
the UN secretary-general in facilitating the mini-summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
