<HEADLINE> Blair Visits Belfast Seeking to Diffuse Parade Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
made a visit to Northern Ireland on Thursday in an attempt to
avert violence at a controversial parade on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival, Blair first visited one of 10 Catholic churches
attacked by suspected loyalist arsonists Wednesday night and met
parish priest Father John O'Sullivan and toured the devastated St
James's Church near Crumlin, Co Antrim, in west Belfast.
</P>
<P>
He denied the arson attacks were a setback to the peace process
he has spearheaded.
</P>
<P>
"The act of destruction that we see behind, that is the past in
Northern Ireland. We are trying to give the people a future that
leaves these acts of barbarism behind us," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
But his main purpose to visit Northern Ireland was to diffuse
parade tension in the province. Protestant "Orangemen" will defy
an official ban and march through a Catholic area of Drumcree on
the edge of Portadown, southwest of Belfast on Sunday, which is
strongly against by the local Catholics. The parade in the past
two years has sparked riots between the Catholics and Protestants.
</P>
<P>
Blair said he had not come to negotiate over a decision by the
province's independent Parades Commission barring the Orangemen
from parading along the Catholic Garvaghy Road in Drumcree.
</P>
<P>
"That's not something I can do," Blair said. "What I can do is
to ask people to listen to the voice of reason...the best thing
that can possibly happen is that people come together and agree."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister is also due to visit Northern Ireland's new
power-sharing assembly, which opened its doors on Wednesday and
elected a pro-British Protestant as its first minister and a
Catholic nationalist as his deputy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
