<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Wheat Production To Be Second Only To Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- World wheat production is now
forecast at 598m. tons, 6m. more than last month and second only
to the record 609m. in 1997, International Grains Council (IGC)
announced here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The revision is attributed to higher figures to Australia,
China, India, Pakistan, Turkey and the United States.
</P>
<P>
However, prospects for trade declined further over the past
month, with larger domestic harvests reducing import requirements
in several countries, especially India and Pakistan, according to
IGC.
</P>
<P>
World wheat consumption is put at 1m. higher at 600m. tons, or
12m. more than last season. Feed use is expected to rise by about
2m. to 100m tons.
</P>
<P>
The forecast for world wheat stocks is 129m. a decline of 2m.
from 1997/98, the Council said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
