<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Abiola Wants to Go Home: Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Visiting United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan Thursday confirmed that he met with
detained Moshood Abiola Tuesday privately.
</P>
<P>
According to Annan, Abiola, widely believed to have won the
annulled June 12, 1993 presidential polls, indicated his
intention "to go home and continue with his life" after in
detention for four years, the News Agency of Nigeria reported.
</P>
<P>
But the official news agency did not confirm a report earlier
Thursday which quoted Annan as saying that the Nigerian
government had assured him the release of all the political
detainees, numbered more than 200.
</P>
<P>
Annan said in Abuja, capital of Nigeria, that Abiola now was
"more realistic on the problems of the country than others
outside."
</P>
<P>
According to him, the opposition leader told him that he had
no knowledge of the events in the country in the past four years
and that he would need to go home and know what the situation is.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief said that Abiola informed him that "he would be
naive to think that he would just come out of detention and
become the president just like that."
</P>
<P>
After the sudden death of Nigeria's former military ruler
General Sani Abacha on June 8, the country has come to a
crossroads.
</P>
<P>
The new head of state, General Abdulsalam Abubakar, has said
that he will continue the current transition to civil rule
program in the way which will come out of the wide consultations
with various interest groups across the country.
</P>
<P>
Opposition groups in the country have mounting pressures for
the release of Abiola to lead a government of national unity.
</P>
<P>
Annan arrived in Nigeria Monday for consultations with
Nigerian leaders on the country's transition to democracy
program.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Nigeria, he also held wide-ranging
consultations with segments of the society, including traditional
rulers, politicians, women leaders, labor, employers, the media,
industrialists and individuals.
</P>
<P>
He said he also met General Abubakar, members of the
Provisional Ruling Council which is the highest decision-making
body of the country, ministers and the National Electoral
Commission of Nigeria as well as some former Nigerian heads of
state, including the just released General Olusegun Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
"I found total unanimity on a number of important issues" in
the meetings with Nigerians, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Among these issues, he said, were an insistence on a return to
democracy, a transition in which Nigerians can have confidence, a
peaceful, democratic and above all credible process leading to
free and fair elections.
</P>
<P>
"All Nigerians want to live under the rule of law, with full
respect for human rights, including freedom of expression and
association," Annan said, adding that "everyone I met wants the
military to return to its proper role in a democratic society."
</P>
<P>
He also said that everyone wants the remaining political
prisoners and detainees including Lt.-Gen. Oladipo Diya and
others to be released.
</P>
<P>
"Finally, everyone wants to see an end to Nigeria's political
and economic isolation," the UN secretary-general added.
</P>
<P>
While the UN and the international community stood ready to
assist in finding a solution, said Annan, "the answer to
Nigeria's problems has to be found by Nigerians themselves."
</P>
<P>
According to analysts, Annan, an African secretary-general of
the world body, has been given much credit by Africans to the
handling of the problems in African countries.
</P>
<P>
His mediation in Nigeria's current political crisis is
expected to help find solutions to the problems afflicting the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
