<HEADLINE> LIFFE Sets New June, Half-Year Trading Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The London International Financial
Futures and Options Exchange (LIFFE) traded a record 109,189,502
futures and options contracts during the first half of 1998,
representing an 8 percent increase on the first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The LIFFE announced here Thursday that it traded its busiest
June ever, trading a record 18,136,592 futures and options
contracts, 6 percent up on June 1997.
</P>
<P>
Average daily trading volume amounted to 824,391 futures and
options contracts, representing an average daily nominal turnover
of 248 billion pounds (396.8 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Jack Wigglesworth, the LIFFE's chairman, said, "LIFFE continues
to see sharp growth in its short-term interest rate contracts (up
61 percent year to date), helped by increasing volatility in
EMU-out products."
</P>
<P>
"In the run-up to EMU, LIFFE has 99 percent market share of
Europe's largest futures contract -- The Three Month Euromark," he
added.
</P>
<P>
In June, the LIFFE announced the transfer of its Five Year Gilt,
German Government Bond (Bund) and Italian Government Bond (BTP)
contracts to its Automated Pit Trading (APT) system in response to
member demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
