<HEADLINE> IFC Invests in Water Treatment Facility in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) Thursday announced the approval of a 25 million
U.S. dollar loan for Binh An Water Corporation Lt. (BAWC) to
construct and operate the first private water treatment facility
in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
BAWC will undertake the project on a Build-Operate-Transfer
(BOT) basis under a 20-year contract with the People's Committee
and the Water Supply Company of Ho Chi Minh City in southern
Vietnam. The treated water will be sold to the Water Supply
Company. By helping to ensure the efficient supply of clean water
to the entire city, BAWC is likely to have an important
demonstration effect.
</P>
<P>
Ho Chi Minh City is Vietnam's largest city with an estimated
population of over 5 million. Current average water usage by
residents is 140 liters a day and is expected to increase to 180
liters a day by 2001. When the plant is completed in 1999, it will
supply 100,000 cubic meters a day of treated water, representing
an estimated 11 percent to the city's water supply.
</P>
<P>
The IFC's financing package consists of a loan of up to 12.5
million dollars for its own account and a syndicated loan of up to
12.5 million dollars for the account of commercial banks and
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The IFC is a member of the World Bank Group, and also the
largest multilateral source for private sector projects for
developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
