<HEADLINE> Museveni Gives Nod to Land Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has given his consent to the land bill which was passed by the
parliament on Monday after making various amendments.
</P>
<P>
Museveni gave his approval Wednesday evening in the southern
Mpigi district.
</P>
<P>
The land bill, which has made headlines for quite a long time
in this east African country, was presented to the president
after staying on the table of the parliament for eight days for
amendment and enlargement.
</P>
<P>
When commenting the land bill, the Prime Minister Kintu Musoke
said: "I am very happy. This is the first time in my lifetime
for a land law in this country to be debated and passed by a
democratically-elected body."
</P>
<P>
The bill passed by the parliament is reported to be
fundamentally different from the original one that was introduced
in March to a lot of controversy. It has 93 sections as opposed
to the original which had 72.
</P>
<P>
The legislation of the bill provides for security of tenure of
the bona fide and lawful occupants while at the same time
recognizing freehold and lease holders.
</P>
<P>
It further elevates customary land tenure to the same status
as freehold.
</P>
<P>
The land bill also establishes mechanism for settling land
disputes at local levels and entitles the land owners whose land
has been taken by government for the resettlement of other people
to compensation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
