<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Admits HARM Missile Missed Iraqi Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Pentagon admitted Thursday
that a U.S. missile fired by F-16 fighter Tuesday failed to hit
its target -- an Iraqi radar site in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The high-speed anti-radiation missile, or HARM, "likely
impacted in a remote area near the radar site in the vicinity of
Al Basra," said Pentagon spokesman Marine Lt. Col Patrick Sivigny.
</P>
<P>
"We do not expect to locate the precise impact location," he
added.
</P>
<P>
U.S officials have said that the F-16 fighter fired the HARM
missile at the radar site Tuesday as its pilot received signal
that four British Tornadoes conducting patrol missions over the
no-fly zone in southern Iraq were locked on by the Iraqi radar.
</P>
<P>
But Iraq dismissed the U.S. statements as mere "lies."
</P>
<P>
"The American officials know that they are telling their people
and the world public opinion lies because they know that the
missile landed in a demilitarized zone near the city of Umm Qasir
in which there were no Iraqi radars or military units," said a
spokesman for the Iraqi Ministry of Culture and Information.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon, trying to head off Iraq's condemnation, cited
several possible reasons why the missile missed the Iraqi target.
</P>
<P>
One reason may have been a failure by the HARM, which homes in
on a source of radiation, to lock onto the site's radar
"signature," but the radar might have quickly switched off after
illuminating the British aircraft, Sivigny said. "Or there may be
other factors," he said without elaboration.
</P>
<P>
U.S officials assumed that the Tuesday incident was an isolated
event rather than the start of any new military challenge to the
no-fly zones, imposed by the United States and its allies since
the Gulf War in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
