<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy to Have More Talks With Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government will start
another round of diplomacy to resolve the conflict in Kosovo, with
mediator Richard Holbrooke returning to Belgrade Friday.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, nominated last month by President Bill Clinton to be
U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, would meet Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic for a cease-fire in Kosovo, said
State Department spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Robert Gelbard, the special envoy on the Balkans,
will also go back to the region while U.S. Ambassador to Belgrade
Chirstopher Hill was meeting Kosovo Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova
in the Kosovo capital of Pristina Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Rubin described the new U.S. initiative as a "full-court
diplomatic press."
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke will press Milosevic "to pull back his forces, stop
the crackdown, stop the use of heavy military equipment, and start
the use of the good sense of negotiations to resolve this
problem," said Rubin.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Rubin signaled the administration has eased its
demand for an immediate withdrawal of Serb forces in Kosovo. He
stressed there should be a cease-fire first before the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
That may ensure that ethnic Albanian fighters do not seize the
opportunity of a troop withdrawal to rush in to fill the vacuum
and gain more territory in Kosovo, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"As a practical matter, we don't expect to see that kind of
pullback in the absence of a cease-fire. That doesn't mean we
wouldn't prefer to see it without a cease-fire, but as a practical
matter, that in our view, is the most likely sequence," he added.
</P>
<P>
The shift was the second major move by the administration in
the past week to try to revitalize its diplomatic approach to the
conflict between Serbs and ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Rubin said the dialogue between the ethnic Albanian
leadership and Belgrade should be open to the armed Albanian
insurgents who had been denounced previously as acting like
terrorists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
