<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CNN, Time Retract Report on Vietnam Nerve Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Cable News Network (CNN)
Television and Time Magazine Thursday retracted a report that the
U.S. military used Sarin nerve gas to kill American defectors
during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
CNN said its internal investigation concluded that its June 7
broadcast on the 1970 Tailwind operation in Laos "cannot be
supported."
</P>
<P>
"There is insufficient evidence that Sarin or any other deadly
gas was used," CNN News Group Chairman Tom Johnson said in a
statement. "Furthermore, CNN cannot confirm that American
defectors were targeted or at the camp."
</P>
<P>
He said Cable News Network acknowledged "serious faults in the
use of the sources who provided... the original reports and
therefore retract the Tailwind story. We apologize to our viewers
and to our colleagues at Time for this mistake."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Time Magazine made a similar statement. "Like CNN,
Time is retracting the story and apologizing for running it," Time
managing editor Walter Isaacson said. "Based on our own
investigation and that concluded by CNN, we have concluded that
the facts simply do not support the allegations that were made."
</P>
<P>
CNN and Time report said U.S. forces used Sarin gas in Laos
during Operation Tailwind to kill American soldiers who had
deserted and the gas was used by U.S. forces in about 20
operations during the war.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon stated that it had found no evidence of any use of
Sarin gas in Operation Tailwind or any evidence of any mission to
go after U.S. Vietnam War defectors.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen ordered an investigation in
response to the report by CNN and Time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
