<HEADLINE> U.S. Sends Mission to Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States will send a
mission to Nigeria and discuss political transition issues with
its new leader Gen. Abdulasalam Abubakar, the State Department
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of the visit is to offer our support for the new
leadership's recent release of political prisoners and to discuss
steps we think could facilitate the transition to democratic
civilian government in Nigeria," spokesman James Rubin told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The mission, led by Under Secretary of State Thomas Pickering,
will leave Washington for Nigeria on the weekend and meet Abubakar
on July 7.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the United States welcomed recent announcements by
Nigeria's new government that all political prisoners will soon be
released. "The release of political prisoners could be a key step
in the transition to civilian government," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. mission has originally scheduled its visit to Nigeria
in June, but called the trip off because the late Nigerian
President Sani Abacha set some preconditions which Washington
deemed unacceptable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
