<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Investors Renew Interest in Emerging Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. investors renewed their
interest in equities of emerging markets in the first quarter this
year, the U.S. Security Industry Association reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Net U.S. purchases of securities from these markets hit 2.8
billion U.S. dollars, sharply reversing the net sales posture of
401 billion dollars in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
Among foreign markets, Asian emerging markets attracted 2.5
billion dollars in equities from U.S. investors, accounting for
the strongest quarter since 3.3 billion dollars recorded in the
first quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Among other key findings, foreign investment in U.S. equities
rose to a record high of 29 billion dollars in the first quarter,
but foreign investors shifted sharply away from U.S. Treasuries
towards corporate bonds and other securities, ending a
three-year-long opposite trend.
</P>
<P>
With nearly 800 securities firms as members, the Security
Industry Association covers 90 percent of the securities business
done in North America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
