<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR Asks for Immediate Access to 150,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees (UNHCR) has asked the government of Guinea for
immediate access to camps housing more than 150,000 Sierra Leonean
refugees, cut off from humanitarian aid for almost three weeks.
</P>
<P>
In a letter dated July 3 to President Lansana Conte of Guinea,
UNHCR chief Mrs Sadako Ogata requested the authorities to re-open
roads to refugee sites near the border with Sierra Leone so that
UNHCR and other aid agencies can deliver desperately needed food,
water and medical care.
</P>
<P>
"The refugees' situation is all the more preoccupying because
they arrived in Guinea in very poor health, and the already-high
mortality rates are likely to reach even more alarming levels
because of this interruption of our aid operation," she said.
</P>
<P>
The area bordering Sierra Leone, to the southwest of the
Guinean town of Gueckedou, has been off-limits for aid deliveries
since June 15, according to UNHCR. Local officials have cited
security concerns in denying access.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR and the World Food Program have been racing to stabilize
the health and nutritional situation of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
"Malnutrition and mortality, particularly among young children,
were already very high before the aid cut-off," said UNHCR. "Many
of those crossing into Guinea in the last weeks had not received a
first food ration when access was blocked."
</P>
<P>
UNHCR warned that work on latrines and clean water supply has
also stopped, raising the risk of disease in dozens of sites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
