<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Higher For 8th Straight Day in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices finished higher for the
eighth straight day in Tokyo Friday as brisk speculation and still
more purchases by foreign investors countered selling by
brokerages after recent rises.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 39.66 points, or 0.24
percent, from Thursday's close to end at 16,511.24.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
issues on the First Section, however, slipped 2.10 points or 0.17
percent to 1,268.36.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to an estimated 581
million shares from Thursday's 924.43 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei extended its impressive streak of gains to eight
trading days stemming back to June 24, and has picked up 1,456.64
points during that period.
</P>
<P>
Trading was erratic in the morning and afternoon sessions. The
Nikkei plunged by more than 160 points just minutes after the
opening bell, but quickly regained most of that as investors
snapped up attractively priced technology shares.
</P>
<P>
The index later dropped to a session low of 16,289.66 early in
the afternoon, but then jumped to a high of 16,625.42 on news that
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto suggested during an
election campaign speech that a permanent income tax cut may take
place next year.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,332 issues listed on the First Section, losers edged
gainers 630 to 532, with 126 issues remaining unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar moved lower
against the yen after the Japanese currency was given a boost by
Hashimoto's verbal support for tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was quoted at 139.23-25 yen at 5 p.m. (local time),
down from 140.55-58 yen at 9 a.m., and from 140.65-75 yen late
Thursday in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
