<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Rejects Criticism By Malaysian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 3 (Xinhua) -- A Singapore Foreign Ministry
spokesman Friday rejected criticism by some Malaysian newspapers
of Singapore's "deliberate exclusion" of Malaysia from a list of
tours offered to participants of a planned international
conference.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the Singapore government has investigated
the matter and found the allegations "completely unfounded."
</P>
<P>
"The misleading and inaccurate allegations that have been made
bear no relationship to the fact and do not contribute to good
bilateral relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, several Malaysian newspapers
reported that the Singapore organizer of Rotary Convention to be
held in the city state next year has excluded Malaysia from a list
of countries to be visited by participants of the planned
convention.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian Rotary Club was quoted by the papers as saying
that the omission of Peninsula Malaysia from the list of tours
offered to participants in the convention brochure was an
"oversight which can be rectified."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the brochure prepared by an American company
that acts as operator of pre- and post-convention tours has given
prominence to East Malaysia and still mentioned West Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"Far from being excluded, Malaysia has been more than
adequately promoted in other ways as a pre- and post-conference
destination," the spokesman said, adding Malaysia was specifically
promoted as a tourist destination at related meetings for the
scheduled 1999 Singapore Rotary conference.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that the Singapore Tourism Board routinely
encourages major convention organizers holding events in Singapore
to offer pre- and post-conference tours to neighboring
destinations including Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Foreign Minister S. Jayakumar, while answering
questions in parliament earlier this week, acknowledged that there
were some outstanding matters being under negotiations between the
two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the two neighboring countries have not
reached agreement on extending water supply to Singapore beyond
the expiry dates of the present water agreements and on the
development of Malayan Railway Land in Singapore as well as the
withdrawal conditions for West Malaysian's Central Provident Fund
savings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
