<HEADLINE> Iranian Official Says No Talks With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Judiciary Supervisor-General
Ayatollah Mohammad Yazdi stated on Friday Iran would not talk on
relations with the United Sates as far as Washington continues its
"hegemonistic and arrogant policies."
</P>
<P>
Yazdi made the remark at the Friday prayer congregation on
Tehran University campus on the anniversary of the downing of
Iranian air passenger by the U.S. in July, 1988, killing 290
passengers aboard.
</P>
<P>
This was the most shameful measure committed by the
U.S. against the Iranian people, the Iranian official news agency
IRNA quoted him as saying, adding that "it would be wrong to
assume that Iranian people would easily forget the tragic event."
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, the U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
voiced Washington's readiness to explore ways to rebuild
confidence with Tehran in order to resume relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
However, Iran replied that the U.S. needs to take concrete
actions instead of good words to prove its sincerity in relations
with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration has never apologized to Iran for the
downing of the airliner which had been taken for a jet fighter,
but terming it as a mistake. It even awarded a medal of bravery to
the commander of the warship which shot down the Iranian plane,
Iranian officials have frequently criticized.
</P>
<P>
However, the case of reparations for Iranian victims is nearly
completed, the official in charge of the case Eftekhar Jahromi
said on Wednesday, so far 220 of the victims' families have
received reparations while the files concerning 14 others are
being completed.
</P>
<P>
Nine other files relating to the case have been sent to the
Swiss embassy which takes charge of the American interests in
Iran, he said, and the families of five victims have not made a
claim yet.
</P>
<P>
Jahromi said that a total of 54.45 million U.S. dollars have
so far been paid to the victims' families and 40 million dollars
as compensation for the downed airplane. 
</P>
</TEXT>
