<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Calls for Stabilized Small-Scale Farmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Friday urged the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) member countries to
stabilize small-scale farmer production.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Vice-President Christon Tembo said, "It is the duty of
governments to facilitate the creation of such an environment"
for the stabilized small scale farmer production because small
scale farmers "cannot do much in brightening about such an
environment."
</P>
<P>
In a opening speech at the meeting of SADC Ministers of Food,
Agriculture and Natural Resources here, he called on the member
countries to make a credit facility accessible to the small scale
famers and create a ready market for farm produce.
</P>
<P>
He also called on governments to provide the farmers with
appropriate technologies, basic rural infrastructure, such as
reasonable feeder roads, food storage facilities and low cost
irrigation systems.
</P>
<P>
The small scale farmers, who comprise the majority of the
farmers in the region, should be engaged in the cash economy, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Tembo also called on the farmers to move from over-dependence
on the government to a position where the use of the resources
generate adequate returns.
</P>
<P>
"Our farmers must be helped to engage in agriculture as a
business. they must look at agriculture as an enterprise with
opportunity cost in terms of the usage of their labor," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The SADC region is endowed with an adequate agricultural
resource base which, hitherto, has been largely under-utilized.
We need to mobilize resources to effectively tap this
agricultural resource base for the benefit of our people," Tembo
noted.
</P>
<P>
At least 30 percent of the total population of the SADC region
directly depends on agriculture for their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
The current forecasts (in June) suggest 16 million tons maize
will be available for this year, about a five percent decline
over 17 million tons last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Regional production of all cereals combined amounts to 21.55
million tons, lower than last year's 22 million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
