<HEADLINE> Canadian Energy Earnings Predicted to Drop 78 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Profits of Canada's 106 largest oil
and gas companies are predicted to plunge 78 percent this year,
said an industry study released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Depressed crude oil prices are the main culprit behind the
pessimistic forecast by Calgary-based investment dealer
FirstEnergy Capital Corp.
</P>
<P>
It predicted that the profits will probably fall to 500 million
Canadian dollars (340 million U.S. dollars) in 1998, from 2.25
billion Canadian dollars (1.53 billion U.S. dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
The companies in the study were responsible for about 80
percent of Canada's daily conventional oil and gas output in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Martin Molyneaux, an analyst at FirstEnergy who headed the
comprehensive study, said the bright spot in the industry is
natural gas.
</P>
<P>
With natural gas prices hovering around 2.10 Canadian dollars
(1.43 U.S. dollars) for 1,000 cubic feet in Alberta, western
Canada, or 30 percent higher than a year ago, companies with large
gas reserves in their portfolio remain in good shape.
</P>
<P>
However, the 28-percent drop in oil prices, to 14.50
U.S. dollars a barrel over the past year, has slashed cash flow at
energy companies, hampering efforts by oil-dependent producers to
strengthen their natural gas drilling programs.
</P>
<P>
FirstEnergy forecasts in its survey that conventional oil and
liquids production among the companies will fall by 120,000
barrels a day, or about seven percent, to 1.63 million barrels a
day this year.
</P>
<P>
Natural gas production is expected to be 11.3 billion cubic
feet a day in 1998, matching last year's output.
</P>
<P>
FirstEnergy expects a rebound in oil prices in the second half
of the year, amounting to an average of 16.50 U.S. dollars for
1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
