<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shipbreaking Thriving in Bangladesh's Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The shipbreaking industry operating
along Bangladesh's southeast coastal belt in Sitakundu has opened
up a potential economic front for the country, the Daily Star
newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The industry earned the local government about 3 billion taka
(about 65.2 million U.S. dollars) annually, the Daily Star said.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of shops have sprung up on both sides of the
Chittagong-Dhaka highway near Sitakundu's shipbreaking yards,
selling goods from scrapper ships, the English newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The sector was brought by the local government under its tax
net only five years ago after taking real shape in early 1980. But
the business started in as early as 1960 when a foreign ship ran
aground in a cyclone and the crew put it up for auction after
failing to refloat it.
</P>
<P>
"Everything of a scrapped ship is utilized and nothing left
un-used," sources of the Shipbreakers Association were quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The rerolling mills in Bangladesh now get 90 percent of their
raw materials from ship-scraps, thus reducing the dependence on
imported billets.
</P>
<P>
The furniture, sanitary facilities, electrical equipment,
fuels, engines, generators, motors and cables from broken ships
are re-used, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
Since shipbreaking is a labor-intensive industry as everything
is done manually, about 1 million people including 300,000
laborers are involved directly or indirectly in the business
thriving over a 20-kilometer-long coastal belt.
</P>
<P>
Costs of imported ships for scrapping range from 100 to 700
million taka (about 2.17-14.98 million dollars) for each one.
</P>
<P>
As the price of scrapped ships has dropped on the international
market to below 175 dollars per ton against 190-261 dollars per
ton earlier, shipbreakers can make more profit.
</P>
<P>
However, modern technologies for breaking the ships, equipping
the yards with floating cranes, barges and dockyards, have yet to
be introduced in Bangladesh, they said, urging the government to
come forward to develop the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
