<HEADLINE> Philippines to Limit Domestic Borrowings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will limit
its remaining domestic borrowings this year to a maximum of 30
billion pesos (750 million U.S. dollars), Finance Secretary
Edgardo Espiritu said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The revised domestic borrowing level is about 25 percent of the
government's earlier committed borrowings for the remainder of the
year.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu explained that the reduction is intended to bring down
interest rates which in the past two weeks have been going up
following market perception that government needs to borrow more
funds from the private sector to finance its budgetary deficit.
</P>
<P>
As of May this year, the government posted a budget deficit of
15.4 billion pesos (385 million dollars). The government is
expected to incur a total of nearly 40 billion pesos (1 billion
dollars) in its budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
Because of low revenue collection, the government has been
forced to source funds from the private sector through the
issuance of government securities, specifically the short-term
Treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
Under the present borrowing program, the government is
scheduled to borrow at least 24 billion pesos (600 million
dollars) a month alone.
</P>
<P>
But aside from reducing its domestic borrowings, Espiritu said
the government is studying the possibility of granting a new round
of tax amnesty to boost government collection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
