<HEADLINE> Sam Rainsy Urges Armed Forces to Keep Neutral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's main opposition
leader Sam Rainsy Friday appealed to the armed forces, police and
security forces to remain neutral during and after the elections.
</P>
<P>
Sam Rainsy, president of the Sam Rainsy Party, urged these
forces not to side with any party.
</P>
<P>
He urged them to help preserve peace and freedom for the
Cambodian people and to avoid using violence against people, or
following illegal orders.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the former finance minister said if the election
results were certified as free and fair by the international
community, he hoped the forces would be ready to defend the new
government by all legal means if necessary.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian government will mobilize a force of about 80,000
to ensure the security of the elections scheduled for July 28.
</P>
<P>
Some political analysts see the elections as just a three-way
contest between Sam Rainsy, who founded his own political party in
1995, and Prince Norodom Ranariddh and Second Prime Minister Hun
Sen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
