<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangxi Cites Success in Fighting Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region has made unprecedented achievements in its fight
against illegal drugs in recent years, according to local police.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 the autonomous region spent more than 30 million yuan
setting up 63 compulsory rehabilitation centers, in which more
than 20,000 drug addicts received treatment.
</P>
<P>
Police sources also disclosed that, in 1997, 4,000
rehabilitated drug-abusers who resumed their addiction were sent
to rehabilitation centers.
</P>
<P>
Situated not far from the notorious "Golden Triangle," the
autonomous region has suffered enormously from the international
drug trade which uses the region as a transfer station.
</P>
<P>
In a counterattack, the autonomous region's police have
intensified their anti-drug efforts in recent year, vowing to
transform the autonomous region into a "no-drug region."
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that police cracked 9,728 drug cases in 1997,
detaining 12,464 drug dealers and seizing 368.46 kilograms of
drugs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. President Leaves Hong Kong for Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton left
here for home Friday evening, winding up his nine-day visit to
China.
</P>
<P>
The special plane carrying the president and the first lady
took off at 20:20 local time (12:20 GMT) from the new Hong Kong
International Airport, which was officially opened by Chinese
President Jiang Zemin at a grand ceremony Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) and his wife Betty Tung went to the
airport to see the president and Mrs. Clinton off.
</P>
<P>
Clinton came to Hong Kong, the last stop of his China visit,
Thursday evening and attended a banquet hosted by Tung Chee Hwa
and his wife Betty Tung in honor of the president and Mrs.
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Friday morning, Clinton made an address to 900 business leaders
at an event organized by the Hong Kong Trade Development Council
and the American Chamber of Commerce in Hong Kong, stressing the
importance of the relationship between the U.S. and all of Asia.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, the first sitting U.S. president to visit Hong Kong,
wrapped up his China visit saying that he had see remarkable
changes in China and that the ties between the United States and
China were terribly important at a press conference he gave at the
hotel he was staying Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Before coming to Hong Kong, Clinton and his party had visited
northwest China's Xi'an, capital city Beijing, China's biggest
industrial center Shanghai and southwest China's tourist resort
Guilin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
