<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNITA Warned for Renewed Military Actions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Venancio de Moura, the Angolan
Foreign Minister, has warned the opposition force for renewed
military actions against the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol, saying
that the government would not remained "indifferent".
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Madrid Wednesday on his way back home after his
mediation effort in Guinea Bissau, Moura said that the Angolan
government would not bear to see the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) recapture cities and towns they
had handed over to the government, neither would the government
bear to to see UNITA continue lay mines on roads and land that
had been cleared of the vital explosives.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government has not yet the intention to have
the armed forces involved in the unrest, but the national police
force have been ordered to strike back on the UNITA military
remnants and other criminal forces if needed.
</P>
<P>
The minister also asked UN member countries, especially those
where UNITA has opened bank accounts and with those UNITA had
diamond trade to observe the sanctions the UN has imposed on
UNITA.
</P>
<P>
UNITA earns from diamond exportation about 500 million U.S.
Dollars each year, which Moura said, had neither been used for
the country's development nor deposited in Angola's banks.
</P>
<P>
He said some neighbors of Angola have been used for UNITA's
arms and diamond trade, though their governments might not be
involved.
</P>
<P>
Moura said that he was pessimistic about the situation in
Angola, adding that though dialogues have been taken as priority
in solving the crisis, there still exists the possibility of
a renewed war.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
