<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Stocks Close Lower as Yen Weakens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks fell 2.56
percent on Friday due to profit-taking moves amid higher interbank
rates caused by a renewed weakening of the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index lost 226.85 points to close at 8,639.31
on Friday. This brought about a 0.4 percent gain in the trading
of a holiday-shortened week. The market was closed on Wednesday,
a public holiday marking Hong Kong's handover to China on July 1
last year.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index lost 99.78 points, or 1.13 percent, to open
at 8,766.38 on Friday and it fell 205.44 points, or 2.32 percent,
to close at 8,660.72 at midday.
</P>
<P>
The day's trading registered a turnover of 4,513 million HK
dollars (578 million U.S. dollars), 3,469 million HK dollars (445
million U.S. dollars) less than on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong stock prices rose 323.06 points, or 3.78 percent, to
close at 8,866.16 on Thursday. 
</P>
