<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MOFTEC Issues White Paper on Foreign Trade (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign trade and economic
cooperation activities will face severe challenges this year
despite the monumental achievements recorded in 1997, according to
the 1998 White Paper recently issued by the Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
The White Paper points to lingering domestic and international
difficulties from past few years, and notes that the impact of the
Asian financial crisis should under no account be underestimated.
</P>
<P>
China's 1998 exports to major trade partners, including members
countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN),
the Republic of Korea (ROK) and Japan, will face even greater
difficulties, the document predicts, while the competitiveness of
Chinese export commodities will decline and China's use of foreign
investments will fall.
</P>
<P>
It also says China will follow the evolution of the financial
crisis in a bid to find and use any opportunities surrounding the
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, The White Paper reviews the growth of China's foreign
trade and economic cooperation in 1997, as well as the economic
and trade development worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The role China's foreign trade and economic cooperation played
in terms of the national economy was further strengthened during
1997, and China was for the first time included on the list of the
world's top ten trading nations, according to the document.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MOFTEC Issues White Paper on Foreign Trade (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's major achievements included an 8.47 percent rise in the
use of foreign investment to 45.26 billion US dollars; steady
progress concerning the reform on the form of providing foreign
trade and the work in this regard, marked results in foreign
economic cooperation; new progress in implementing the diversified
market strategy and reform of the foreign trade system; and the
continuous development of both multilateral and bilateral economic
and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
The global economy grew rapidly by 4.1 percent during 1997,
according to the document. It also predicted that the global
economy will continue to grow during 1998, although anticipated
3.5 percent growth will be the lowest since 1994.
</P>
<P>
The global economic increase rate will slow dramatically, and
the Asian financial crisis will have a definite impact on the
global economy.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the 1998 increase rate for international trade
will drop, and the growth rate for the global trade volume is
expected to fall by some two to three percent on the 1997 figure,
according to the White Paper.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it acknowledges that the trade imbalance will
intensify competition amongst traders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
