<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest Female Giant Panda Dies in Shanxi Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Shasha, China's oldest female giant
panda, died yesterday in the Taiyuan Zoo at age 33 from heart
failure and cerebral blockage.
</P>
<P>
Shasha, one of the few giant pandas to live past age 25,
suffered from heart failure and stopped breathing during the night
on June 29. Veterinarians immediately administered emergency
medical procedures to restart her heart.
</P>
<P>
Local veterinarians and zookeepers used state-of-the-art
equipment and rendered constant care over the ensuring four days
to save Shasha.
</P>
<P>
However, one veterinarian noted that prolonging the panda's
life using existing medical procedures was impossible due to
Shasha's age and medical condition.
</P>
<P>
A zoo doctor said that Shasha was suffering from epilepsy and
cataracts resulting from her advanced age.
</P>
<P>
Temperatures soaring to 37 degrees Celsius on the night
Shasha collapsed further complicated the problem.
</P>
<P>
Shasha never regained consciousness, with only medicines and
oxygen prolonging her life for four days.
</P>
<P>
The zoo plans to complete taxidermy procedures and place
Shasha's body on display. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
