<HEADLINE> Australian Shares Close Slightly Firmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market clawed
back earlier losses to record a slightly firmer close Friday in a
quiet session of trade ahead of the Independence Day long weekend
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index finished 0.4 points higher
at 2,743.1, up from an intra-day low of 2,724.4.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said the local bourse was "pretty dead largely due to
the fact that not much happened with the Dow last night."
</P>
<P>
"We won't get a lead from the U.S. now until next Monday
night," a Brisbane-based dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Last night the Dow Jones Industrial Average was dragged 23.41
points lower to 9,025.26, on the back of a slump in technology
stocks and profit-taking by investors looking to cash in on the
market's recent climb.
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo, the Nikkei managed to add just 39 points to 16,511.0.
</P>
<P>
The Australian industrials sector rose 3.3 points to 4,810.7
and the all resources dipped 2.6 to 1,075.3.
</P>
<P>
Market heavyweight News Corp. came off 18.5 cents, its
preferred scrip eased 3.1, Coles Myer improved 13 cents, fellow
retailer Woolworths lost two cents.
</P>
<P>
BHP shed 11 cents to 14.09 Australian dollars, Rio Tinto
slipped 17.4, WMC eased seven, Woodside moved back four, MIM was
steady at 83 cents, zinc miner and smelter Pasminco Ltd. rose 9
cents or 7 percent to 1.36 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index edged down 4.6 points to 1,113.4 as the spot
price for gold bullion in Sydney was selling an ounce 1.50 U.S.
dollars lower at 295.90.
</P>
<P>
NAB led the banking index 32.5 points higher to 5,905.
</P>
<P>
Westpac rose 5.2 cents, ANZ dipped two and Commonwealth Bank
eased 10 cents.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 298.64 million shares worth 943.03
million Australian dollars (582.80 million U.S. dollars) with
rises outnumbering falls 522 to 504. 
</P>
