<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Blames Palestinians for Gaza Standoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu Friday accused the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
of "deliberate provocation" in the standoff between Israeli and
Palestinian troops in Gaza Strip Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before a regular briefing to foreign
diplomats on the political situation, Netanyahu described the
Palestinian blockade of a coastal road and several Jewish
settlements as a " major violation" of the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
He slammed a senior PNA official for attempting to challenge
the Israeli rights over security mandated in the signed
agreements.
</P>
<P>
He was apparently referring to PNA Minister of Supplies Abdul
Aziz Shahin, who led the Palestinians in the 12-hour standoff
that ended early Friday morning following intensive mediating
efforts involving American and Egyptian officials.
</P>
<P>
During the dispute over the use of a coastal road, Israeli and
Palestinian troops scuffled and shouted with each other, and even
took key positions where they pointed guns at one another.
</P>
<P>
This was the worst standoff between Israeli and Palestinian
troops since September 1996, when they clashed in a temporary
armed conflict sparked by Israel's opening of an underground
tunnel in the Old City of East Jerusalem. Over 70 people were
killed in the 1996 confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu vowed that Israel would never give up its rights on
security and would not allow the use or threat of use of
violence. "Nothing will be achieved by violence," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the latest incident was another sign of the PNA's
refusal to honor their commitments, including the collection of
illegal weapons, arrest of terrorists, halt to hostile propaganda,
and revision of the Palestinian Covenant calling for the
destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
To move forward the peace process, the Palestinians must keep
their commitments and resolve their differences with Israel
peacefully, Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
The hard-line leader once against blamed the PNA for the long
deadlock in the peace process. He said "some progress" on the
sticking point of Israeli next troop pullback in the West Bank had
been achieved, but the "persistent refusal" by the Palestinians to
fulfill their obligations prevented an overdue agreement.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's standoff came at a time when tension is mounting
between the two sides due to the long impasse over the second
pullback, the recent Israeli decision to expand the boundaries of
Jerusalem, as well as the PNA efforts to upgrade its status in the
United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
