<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Auto-making Countries to Develop Global Regulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of 30 auto-making
countries including Japan and the U.S. as well as the European
Union have reached an agreement for the development of global
technical regulations for motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The new agreement, which will be developed in parallel with the
existing 1958 agreement, was open for signature on June 25,
announced the United Nations Economic Commission for Europe here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, reached after three years of intensive
negotiations, will go into force once it is ratified by a certain
number of countries.
</P>
<P>
Contracting parties to the agreement will be able to propose
rules and regulations ensuring high levels of safety,
environmental protection, energy efficiency and anti-theft
performance to be listed in a Compendium of Candidate Global
Technical Regulations.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the agreement is to establish global technical
regulations through harmonization of existing regulations.
</P>
<P>
Once a regulation is established as global, contracting parties
to the agreement, who voted in its favor, are obligated to adopt
it in its own legislation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa: No Final Decision on Ties With Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is now in the
process of a decision regarding the establishment of diplomatic
relations with Iraq, South African Foreign Ministry Spokesman
Marco Boni told Xinhua Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said in a telephone interview that South Africa is looking
for ways and modalities of such a move, adding: "There is no
final decision."
</P>
<P>
Boni said his country should normalize relations with
countries like Iraq under the context that South Africa will soon
take over the chair of the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM).
</P>
<P>
But he refused to speculate whether the two countries would be
able to establish diplomatic ties before this year's NAM summit,
which will be held between August 29 and September 3 in Durban,
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Boni said South Africa is also considering diplomatic ties
with seven other countries including the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
These countries are all members of the United Nations as South
Africa is, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to South African opposition parties' attack on the
government's approach to Iraq, Boni said: "They have narrow views
of South Africa's international responsibility."
</P>
<P>
He said the establishment of formal relations with countries
where South Africa was previously not represented would offer
opportunities for South Africa to have consular and economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Boni also shrugged off opposition parties's criticism that the
forging of ties with Iraq was ill-timed as South Africa is
shutting down embassies worldwide owing to budget constraint.
</P>
<P>
"To Establish diplomatic relations does not mean opening an
embassy," he said.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of formal relations would allow South Africa
to deal at official level consular, economic and legal issues, he
explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
