<HEADLINE> Mandela to Open Chinese-Built Stadium in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela is to open a Chinese-built stadium located at Namboole,
10 km east of the Ugandan capital of Kampala on January 26, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Eriya Kategaya, the Ugandan First Deputy Prime Minister and
Minister of Foreign Affairs, said this while meeting with Chinese
Ambassador to Uganda Song Zengshou here Thursday, the New Vision
daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said the stadium, built by a Chinese construction firm,
COMPLANT, was handed over to the Ugandan authorities on February
28, 1997 and many football matches as well as some concerts have
been held in this largest stadium in Uganda since.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper report said the date of the ceremony was chosen
to coincide with the National Resistance Movement Day and it will
be presided over by Mandela who retires from presidency in April
1999.
</P>
<P>
The 40,202-seat complex, whose construction work began in
1992, cost as much as 30 billion Uganda Shillings or 30 million
U.S. Dollars. The money was a soft loan from the Chinese
government. 
