<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Cuts External Debt by $43 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's external debt was reduced
by about 43.45 million U.S. Dollars in the first half of this
year, the national newspaper This Day reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the payment was effected through the
debt conversion program established by the government 10 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
However, the amount was plowed back into the Nigerian economy
by way of investment in equities of various companies in
different sectors.
</P>
<P>
The cash gifts and grants sub-sector was the leading
beneficiary of such investment in the January-June period when it
attracted 18.28 million Dollars, accounting for 42.8 percent of
the total funds injected into the economy.
</P>
<P>
It was followed by the manufacturing sub-sector with an
investment of 9.75 million Dollars, the exploration and mining
sub-sector with 7.04 million Dollars, and the hotel and tourism
sub-sector with 3.68 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The report, quoting a study credited to Bankque National de
Paris Eastern European Investment Banking Group, revealed that
Nigeria's foreign debt stands at about 37 billion Dollars and has
been a significant setback to economic development.
</P>
<P>
The Paris Club of creditors accounts for two-thirds of the
total debt in which five billion is projected for servicing
yearly.
</P>
<P>
It was for the purpose of reducing the debt burden that the
Nigerian government launched the debt conversion program in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Between November that year and June this year, 378 investment
applications were successful in converting 799.54 million Dollars
into equity participation in Nigerian companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
