<HEADLINE> Zambia Asks for IMF Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia government has appealed
to the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to help Zambia exploit
the highly indebted poor countries (Hipc) initiative to reduce
its foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Friday quoted acting Finance Minister Alfeyo
Hambayi as saying Thursday here when he received visiting IMF
officials that Zambia needs the Hipc initiative as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
"Under the current arrangements, Zambia will not qualify for
accessing the Hipc benefits until at least three full years under
the country's enhanced structural adjustment facility (Esaf) have
been completed.
</P>
<P>
"This will take us until the end of 1999. Zambia cannot wait
that long to see the burden of its external indebtedness reduced
to manageable levels," said Hambayi.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the IMF to judge the performance of Zambia by
its policy direction rather than isolated incidents, adding that
the support of the IMF is vital to the implementation of the
economic reform program in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Zambia, whose foreign debt now has exceeded 7 billion U.S.
Dollars, has to set aside 60 percent of its foreign exchange
earnings to serve the unsustainable debt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
