<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar drifted a
little lower Friday for a lack of firm news from Japan on
decisions to reform its faltering economy.
</P>
<P>
The local currency ended the session slightly weaker but off
earlier lows at 61.72 U.S. cents from 61.79 late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Japan Thursday night unveiled a vast rescue scheme to tackle
its huge bad bank loans, bowing to international pressure to
revive the world's second largest economy.
</P>
<P>
Under the new bridge bank system insolvent banks will be taken
over and their mountain of bad loans cleaned up.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank senior economist Michael Blythe said he
expected the outlook for the Japanese economy and financial reform
would continue to hold center stage over the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
Colonial State Bank chief economist Craig James said the
Australian dollar was likely to be mired between 0.6000 and 0.6300
U.S. dollar over coming months.
</P>
<P>
"Asia will face a long, grinding recovery with pot-holes along
the road while the recent rally in commodity prices is
unconvincing," James said.
</P>
<P>
At the close the Australian dollar was trading at 85.94
Japanese yen from 85.92 and 1.1213 German marks from 1.1243.
