<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Semiconductor Sales Decrease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The global semiconductor sales
dropped by 12.7 percent in May as compared with the same period of
last year, said the California-based Semiconductor Industry
Association (SIA) on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The sales totaled 9.99 billion U.S. dollars, down from 11.46
billion dollars in May of 1997.
</P>
<P>
"The May numbers reflect the recent announcements from several
leading semiconductor companies," the SIA said.
</P>
<P>
"The semiconductor industry is still responding to the effects
of the slowdown of the Asian economies," it added.
</P>
<P>
The decline touched all four marketing regions -- the Americas,
Europe, Japan and the Asia-Pacific region -- with Japan and the
Americas falling by 19 and 17 percent, respectively, on a
year-by-year basis.
</P>
<P>
Oversupply which continues to depress prices adds up to the
Asian factor. Unit sales are actually climbing, but price cuts are
moving faster, leading to falling revenues.
</P>
<P>
The problem is particularly acute in memory, the core chips
used in computers. Memory prices for the desktop standard
16-megabit chip have fallen some 90 percent in the past three
years, to the point where prices are at or below the cost of
manufacture, some industry analysts say.
</P>
<P>
Another serious problem for chipmaking companies has been the
PC market's move toward lower cost machines, which has slashed the
average selling price of chips.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, chip industry leaders confronting slowing
sales had predicted a rebound by mid-1998. But the recovery did
not come true.
</P>
<P>
The financial services firm Merril Lynch &AMP; Co. now projects
that semiconductor sales will be down between five percent to 10
percent for the year, after originally forecasting that 1998 would
be flat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Stocks Close Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Share Prices closed lower Friday
on Singapore Stock Market as the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials Index (STII) slipped by 2.20 points to close at
1,122.67 points, a strong contrast to the sharp rising in the past
two days.
</P>
<P>
The total volume shrank to 106.49 million shares, valued at
197.58 million Singapore dollars (about 116.91 million U.S.
dollars). The total of gainers dropped to 69 from Thursday's 169.
The number of losers rose to 180 from 110 a day earlier while 340
stocks remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
MBF Land was the most active stock with 17.05 million shares
traded. It was followed by MBF Cap which had 8.04 million units
done. DBS Land was next with 7.06 million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Rothmans M topped the gainers of the day, up 30 cents to 11.70
Singapore dollars at close. Thai PR gained 23 cents to finish at
3.02 U.S. dollars. SPH rose by 20 cents to end at 12.90 Singapore
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creativ 50 was the biggest loser as it lost 50
cents to finish at 21.60 Singapore dollars. Parkway was down 36
cents to end at 3.00 Singapore dollars. Shangri was next as it
shed 31 cents to close at 1.89 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said shares fell early but news of permanent tax cuts
in Japan caused a recovery before the midday break. Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto was quoted as saying that he wanted
permanent income tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
But share prices ended lower, indicating the euphoria over a
potential Japanese tax cut was fading away. Investors soon
realized that the measure alone can not solve the many deep-seated
problems that has been plaguing Japan's economy.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said property counters finished mixed on profit-taking
while some blue chips attracted interests.
</P>
<P>
However, they said, smaller stocks continued to be shunned as
retail investors were absent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
