<HEADLINE> State Development Bank Increases Support for Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) - The State Development Bank (SDB) has
pledged to further intensify credit support for infrastructure
and shorten the assessment process for related projects to
stimulate the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the bank will support a number of
infrastructure projects during 1998. The SDB has already
approved 121 projects and pledged to grant a total of 42.3
billion yuan in related loans.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis in Southeast Asia has had a negative
impact on China's export sector which has long been a major
contributor to the national economy. Therefore, the Chinese
government has decided to increase inputs for fixed assets such as
infrastructure to ensure fulfillment of this year's economic
growth rate of eight percent.
</P>
<P>
The bank, a state policy-oriented bank established to support
infrastructure and basic industries, has set this year's credit
line at 122.8 billion yuan, up 11.6 percent on last year's figure.
</P>
<P>
The bank will also place top priority on railway, highway,
telecommunications, water conservancy, power generation,
environmental protection and urban construction projects.
</P>
<P>
The bank has also pledged to simplify the assessment process
and ensure the early placement of funds for projects with a high
return potential. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
