<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers on Friday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The French supreme court the Cour de Cassation Thursday said
that the 1985 contamination of blood stocks by AIDS would not make
up a crime of poisoning, and thus allow three key members of the
government at that time, including former Prime Minister Laurent
Fabius, who is now National Assembly president, to avoid a trial by
court over the disaster. The court said that a crime of poisoning
must be accompanied with an intention to kill.
</P>
<P>
-- Three years and a half after it joined the European Union,
Austria formally took over the rotating chairmanship of EU from
July 1. However, Vienna's term of chairmanship is overshadowed by
a major event for EU during its presidency -- the German general
elections in September, which is expected to produce a new German
government.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The French Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn said on Thursday
that the growth rate this year in France will be around 3 percent,
close to the 3.2 percent predicted by the official statistics
bureau INSEE. Strauss-Kahn made the statement when presenting the
economic balance sheet for the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
-- The French Academy Thursday for the first time in history
decided to let the General Commission of Terminology and Neologism
to decide whether to feminize some names in the French language. The
French Academy in the past had always been the advisor for the
government in the field of language. 
</P>
