<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Promotes Human Development (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- A report released today by the
United Nations Development Program (UNDP) revealed that China has
an admirable record in promoting human development, with falling
poverty rates and continuing improvements in the health and
educational status of the population.
</P>
<P>
Generally speaking, the China Human Development Report -- 1997
concluded the Chinese citizens enjoy better health, live longer
and are better educated than ever before. Major indicators of
human development such as longevity approach levels in
developed nations.
</P>
<P>
The Report, compiled by well-known scholars from both at home
and abroad, is the first document of its kind to focus on human
development in China.
</P>
<P>
The Report summarizes the history and current status of
sustainable human development in China, focuses on
remaining challenges and offers micro-policy suggestions for
dealing with them.
</P>
<P>
The Report addresses a wide spectrum of human development
issues, including the distribution of income, health care,
education, nutrition, population and migration, the status of
women, employment, social security and the state of the
environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Promotes Human Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Report notes that China faces enormous challenges related
to human development. It also points out that growing
unemployment, rising social and economic inequality, the absence
of a social security system able to cope with changing conditions,
the unequal burden on women due to social changes, and the growing
destruction of China's natural environment are amongst the most
serious threats.
</P>
<P>
The document provides the first ever ranking of the Human
Development Index for all provinces, municipalities and autonomous
regions, with the exception of Taiwan, Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, Beijing and Tianjin rank first through third respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Report predicts that China will eventually overcome the
challenges and enter the new century as a model for both rapid
economic growth and human development which promotes the
well-being of all people and the natural balance of the earth.
</P>
<P>
Ms. Kerstin Leitner, UNDP resident representative in China and
UN resident coordinator for China, pointed to the Report as a
"contribution to China's goal of alleviating poverty."
</P>
<P>
She noted it will also help the Chinese government and people,
as well as foreign partners, understand China's achievements to
date and challenges ahead.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Stock Market Gains in First Half of '98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus stock market soared by 7.8
percent in the first six months of 1998, with the CISCO All-Share
Index closing on June 30 at 419.8 points, a market report said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The market review, issued by the Cyprus Investment and
Securities Corporation Limited (CISCO), said the total volume of
trading in the first half climbed to 173.3 million Cyprus pounds
(about 346.6 million U.S. dollars) from 92.9 million pounds (about
185.8 million dollars) in the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The largest share of the total trading volume remained to be
held by the banking sector, which accounted for 44.4 percent of
all the transactions in the first half of 1998, compared to 42.6
percent for the whole of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the share of total trading by retail companies
climbed to 8.2 percent, or a 3.1 percent rise, while that by the
investment companies rose to 6 percent, up 1.9 percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the share of total trading by the industrial
companies declined by 1.8 percent, while that by the tourist
companies declined by 0.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France's GDP Expected to Grow 3.2 Percent in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- France's gross domestic product (GDP)
is expected to grow at 3.2 percent in 1998, said the official
economic and statistics bureau INSEE on Friday.
</P>
<P>
This growth is stimulated by a growing domestic consumption
which is backed by the creation of some 390,000 new jobs, said the
INSEE.
</P>
<P>
It predicts that the country's unemployment rate will be
lowered to around 11.5 percent by the end of this year, as is
compared with 12.3 percent last December.
</P>
<P>
Employment is improving in all sectors of the economy and will
be the driving force behind the growth, the INSEE said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, demand for investments is strong and long-term
banking interest rates for lending credits to enterprises are
maintained at a low level.
</P>
<P>
The amount of investment in France is expected to grow by 6.4
percent this year as is compared with last year, said the INSEE.
</P>
</TEXT>
