<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Compensates Farmers' Losses by Monkeys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Red Colobus monkeys, a major
tourist attraction in the isles of Zanzibar, have damaged
agricultural crops and forced the government to compensate
farmers.
</P>
<P>
So far, Zanzibar Agriculture, Livestock and Natural Resources
Ministry has compensated villagers around the Jozani Forest 1.5
million Shillings (about 2,250 U.S. Dollars) for the crops
damaged by the monkeys.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by Daily News Friday, the deputy
agriculture minister, Mwalim Ameir, said the money spent on
compensation was part of profits accrued from tourist excursions
into the forest.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question by Haji Mkema, an MP from Koani, in the
House of Representatives in Zanzibar Thursday, Ameir said the
ministry has started taking measures to protect maize, cassava
and other crops.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the official maintained the need to preserve
the red Colobus monkeys, which attract large numbers of tourists.
</P>
</TEXT>
