<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang reaffirms China's stand on Nuclear Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
reiterated here Friday that China favors a comprehensive ban and
total destruction of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
China, unconditionally, will never be the first to use nuclear
weapons against any country or any region, Jiang said at the
five-nation meeting of China, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Russia and
Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
"Under no circumstances will China ever use, or threaten to
use, nuclear weapons against any nuclear-free country or any
nuclear-free zone. China has no intention to resume nuclear
tests," he said.
</P>
<P>
China appreciates Kazakhstan's move to destroy its nuclear
weapons and its position on joining the Treaty on the
Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons and the Comprehensive Nuclear
Test Ban Treaty in the status of a nuclear-free nation, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that China also supports the proposal, which was put
forward by Uzbekistan and supported by the countries in Central
Asia, for the establishment of a Central Asia Nuclear-Free Zone.
</P>
<P>
"China is deeply concerned about the tense situation in South
Asia, which is adjacent to Central Asia. China supports the joint
communique issued in Geneva recently by the five permanent members
of the United Nations Security Council and other relevant
resolutions of the Security Council," the Chinese president said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that China is willing to work together with the
international community to stop the nuclear arms race in South
Asia, to ease the tension in that region and to maintain peace and
security in Asia and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
In order to maintain and develop the friendly cooperation among
our five nations, "we must continue to resolutely fight against
such public evils as national splittism, religious extremism,
terrorism, arms smuggling and drug trafficking, which are
threatening the stability and security of the countries in this
region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that China is willing to actively develop the
economic cooperation among the five nations in light of the
principle of mutual benefit and efficiency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
