<HEADLINE> CPSC Justice Ministers Meeting Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LISBON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The seventh meeting of the justice
ministers from the Community of Portuguese-Speaking Countries
(CPSC) ended here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which opened on June 30 with the theme of
"Economy, Rights and Justice", adopted eight proposals to
strengthen the justice systems in the member countries of the CPSC.
</P>
<P>
The seven justice ministers of the CPSC countries agreed to
strengthen mutual technological assistance and personnel training,
to make restructuring so as to guarantee the management
effectiveness, and to carry out multi-lateral cooperation in
justice, especially in the fields of criminal law, civil law and
commercial law.
</P>
<P>
The CPSC, which was established in Portugal's capital of Lisbon
in July 1997, included Brazil, Portugal, Cape Verde, Guinea
Bissau, Mozambique, Angola, and Sao Tome and Principe.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also decided to hold the eighth justice meeting in
the year 2000 in Sao Tome and Principe with a theme of "Cooperation
and Justice, Estimate and Challenge".
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Chinese Macao also attended the meeting as
an observer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
