<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Meets U.S. Agricultural Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao
pointed out today that the future of China's agriculture lies in
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the nation will increase investments in
agricultural science and technology and accelerate the
industrialization of related research findings.
</P>
<P>
Wen made the remarks during a morning meeting with T.C. Tso, a
Chinese-American agricultural expert and his party which included
Nobel Prize Winner Norman Borlaug, and Professor Ray Wu from
Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
The experts spoke highly of China's great agricultural
achievements and offered constructive views on the nation's
agricultural development.
</P>
<P>
Wen said China's long-term principle places the highest
priority on the role agriculture plays in the national economy and
views the farming sector as the foundation of its economy.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Chinese government attaches great importance
to reform, science and technology, and the construction of
infrastructure for the agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Wen said China will step up infrastructure construction
centering on water conservancy projects and the environment.
</P>
<P>
China, a water-deficient country, will pay special attention to
saving water and combining the development of related resources
with efficient irrigation.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Agriculture Chen Yaobang also attended the
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
