<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maintain Peace and Stability and Promote Development and </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
delivered a speech at the five-nation meeting of China,
Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Russia and Tajikistan here Friday. The
full text reads as follows.
</P>
<P>
Respected Colleagues and Friends:
</P>
<P>
Today, we are glad to be here to discuss ways for further
promoting peace and stability and strengthening the economic
cooperation among our five nations and in this region. I believe
this meeting will be a full demonstration of our sincere will and
firm determination to promote the cause of peace and development.
</P>
<P>
For the sake of safeguarding peace and stability in this
region, China and Russia signed and published a bilateral
agreement that reaffirmed our obligation not to be the first to
use nuclear weapons against each other and pronounced our decision
to stop targeting each other with our strategic nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
China appreciates Kazakhstan's move to destroy its nuclear
weapons and its position on joining the Treaty on the
Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons and the Comprehensive Nuclear
Test Ban Treaty in the status of a nuclear-free nation.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, China solemnly pledged nuclear security assurance to
Kazakhstan and declared it would actively participate in the
process of "The Conference on Interaction and Confidence-Building
Measures in Asia", which was initiated by Kazakh President
Nursultan Nazarbayev.
</P>
<P>
China also supports the proposal, which was put forward by
Uzbekistan and supported by the countries in Central Asia, for the
establishment of a Central Asia Nuclear-Free Zone.
</P>
<P>
Now, I would like to reiterate that China favors a
comprehensive ban and total destruction of nuclear weapons. And
unconditionally, China will never be the first to use nuclear
weapons against any country or any region. Moreover, under no
circumstances will China ever use, or threaten to use, nuclear
weapons against any nuclear-free country or any nuclear-free
zone. China has no intention to resume nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
The achievements our five countries have made in safeguarding
regional peace and stability and in fostering the continuous
development of our mutual relations are the results of our efforts
to go with the tide of the times and uphold the principles of
mutual respect for territorial integrity and sovereignty, mutual
non-interference in each other's internal affairs, and equality
and mutual benefit.
</P>
<P>
Our common experience shows that only with mutual respect can
we live in harmony; only with equality and mutual benefit can we
develop our cooperation; and only when we uphold the principle of
solving the differences and disputes between countries by peaceful
means can we find effective ways for equitable and reasonable
solutions to our problems.
</P>
<P>
In order to maintain and develop the friendly cooperation among
our five nations, we must continue to resolutely fight against
such public evils as national splittism, religious extremism,
terrorism, arms smuggling and drug trafficking, which are
threatening the stability and security of the countries in this
region. In this regard, there is a need for the diplomatic,
police, security, customs and other related departments of our
five countries to strengthen their consultation and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
China is deeply concerned about the tense situation in South
Asia, which is adjacent to Central Asia. China supports the joint
communique issued in Geneva recently by the five permanent members
of the United Nations Security Council and other relevant
resolutions of the Security Council. China is willing to work
together with the international community to stop the nuclear arms
race in South Asia, to ease the tension in that region and to
maintain peace and security in Asia and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
China, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Russia and Tajikistan enjoy many
advantages in fostering their bilateral and multilateral economic,
trade and technological cooperation. China is willing to actively
develop the economic cooperation among our nations in light of the
principle of mutual benefit and efficiency. Here I suggest that we
start with developing our cooperation in the fields of trade,
transport, energy, metallurgy, light industry, textile industry
and agriculture, and encourage mutual investment and joint
production. China will continue to take an active part in the
construction of the Euro-Asia continental bridge and to provide
sea-borne transport facilities to the countries concerned.
</P>
<P>
Thank you.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Yet to Meet Key Demands for IMF Loans: IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has still to try more to
fulfill two key conditions so that the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) can start talks on resuming 205-million-U.S.-Dollar
aid package, the fund's representative Reimer Carstens has said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya needs to strengthen the independence of the
Anti-Corruption Authority and establish accountability for the
so-called Goldenberg export compensation case, he was quoted
Friday by the Kenya Times newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Those two steps would need to be taken by mid-July if there is
to be any chance of an IMF mission coming in August or September,
and if there is any hope of a resumption of IMF aid this calendar
year, Carstens said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
If they are taken, the country could be back on course for a
resumption of the aid loan, he said. The loan was halted on July
31 last year, causing a collapse of investors' confidence and a
sharp rise of interest rates in this east African state.
</P>
<P>
"Assuming these two governance issues, called prior actions,
are accomplished, given the presentation of a courageous budget,
one could say the future cooperation between the fund and Kenya
could be on course very soon," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a tough budget speech at parliament on June 11, Finance
Minister Simeon Nyachae said he aimed to bring the interest rates
down by slashing public spending and to curb mounting budget
deficits in this fiscal year starting July 1.
</P>
<P>
Kenya ran a budget deficit of 2.7 percent of gross domestic
product in the 1997/98 fiscal year, with domestic borrowing
pushing interest rates up very high.
</P>
<P>
Carstens said government sources had told him that work on
fulfilling the two conditions was "well advanced."
</P>
<P>
But if the conditions are not fulfilled this month, a visit
would be delayed until after the annual IMF/World Bank meeting in
October, and any resumption of IMF lending would not be possible
until the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Evangelos Calamitsis, head of the IMF's
African Department, said in Washington that it would be tight to
resume lending in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Businessman Kamlesh Pattni, his Goldenberg company and three
former senior government officials have pleaded not guilty to
charges of stealing billions of Shillings from Kenya's Treasury
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Last week, John Harum Mwau, the chief of the Anti-Corruption
Authority set up last year, brought his first case to court,
charging Nairobi City Council officials with defrauding millions
of Kenyan Shillings from City Hall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
