<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Disappointed at U.S. Airways Orders from Airbus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Boeing Co. Thursday expressed
disappointment over the decision of U.S. Airways Group Inc. to buy
up to 30 wide-bodied jets valued at 3.7 billion U.S. dollars from
rival Airbus Industries.
</P>
<P>
"We are disappointed," Boeing spokeswoman Liz Verdier said, "We
offered what we thought would be the best airplane for their
marketing requirements."
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, U.S. Airways chose the Airbus A330 over
Boeing's 767-400 for the carrier's trans-Atlantic routes. The
initial order is for seven A330s, with seven orders to be
reconfirmed and 16 further options in view.
</P>
<P>
The deal is the second major contract between U.S. Airways and
Airbus -- the former signed an agreement with the latter in 1996
for up to 400 of the smaller A320 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts believe that Thursday's deal underlines the
growing strength of Airbus, which said it won 52 percent of all
firm global commercial airline orders in the first half of 1998 --
the best showing in its 28-year history.
</P>
<P>
Boeing has suffered a rash of problems in recent months,
culminating in a monthlong shutdown on two assembly lines last
October to clear bottlenecks.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Boeing has been badly hit by the Asian crisis,
with airlines in the region struggling to find financing for new
jets.
</P>
<P>
Airbus, by contrast, has hardly been touched by the slump in
Asia orders because many of its best customers operate in Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
