<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tick Diseases Threaten Cattle in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Over 800 cases of various
tick-related diseases have been reported in Zimbabwe since
January this year, endangering the health of thousands of cattle,
the Department of Veterinary Services said.
</P>
<P>
The loss of cattle through tick-related diseases poses a
serious threat to efforts by farmers to rebuild the national
herd.
</P>
<P>
While great strides have been made to control the diseases,
the problem is compounded by the fact that most farmers are
unable to recognize and treat the diseases themselves, the
department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Many more cattle may die if communal, small-holder and
commercial farmers do not vaccinate their cattle.
</P>
<P>
Welbourne Madzima, deputy director of the Department of
Veterinary Services, told the Daily Herald that efforts were
underway to sensitize farmers on the need to vaccinate their
livestock against the diseases.
</P>
<P>
Trends indicated that headwater would eventually cover the
entire country as the disease was spreading to the higher
rainfall areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
The department wants farmers to take precautionary measures by
vaccinating their livestock against tick-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
The disease affects lungs causing difficulty in breathing
while red water and gall sickness caused loss of blood in
breasts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> England Still Lead FIFA Fair Play Award Contest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
PARIS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Despite the sending off of David
Beckham and the elimination in the second round, England still take
the lead in FIFA Fair Play Award contest.
</P>
<P>
Traditionally, the FIFA Fair Play Award is awarded to the team
with the best record of fair play according to a points system and
criteria extablished by the FIFA Fair Play Committee.
</P>
<P>
At the 1994 World Cup finals, the Brazilian team, which
eventually won the World Cup, also won the Fair Play award. That
was their third Fair Play trophy since the award was inaugurated in
1978.
</P>
<P>
Only teams that play at least four matches of the World Cup
finals are eligible to win the award. The overall assessment of a
team during the final competition is calculated by adding the points
attained at each match and dividing this figure by the number of
matches played.
</P>
<P>
England lead the list with 3,311 points, followed by Norway in
the second place at 3,286. Brazil are third with 3,285 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Areas Enjoy Improved Air Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- China's urban areas are enjoying
improved air quality, according to the weekly air quality report
released today by the China Environment Monitoring Center.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen cities -- Guilin, Xiamen, Kunming, Nantong, Wenzhou,
Fuzhou, Nanchang, Nanning, Ningbo, Shantou, Zhuhai, Haikou,
Zhanjiang and Beihai -- enjoyed excellent air quality between June
26 and July 2, with four cities added to the latest report.
</P>
<P>
A total of 22 cities, including Guangzhou, Nanjing and
Chongqing, also enjoyed relatively good air quality during the
period. However, the nitrogen oxide readings in Guangzhou, and the
total volume of suspended particles in Yinchuan, Jinan and
Shijiazhuang remained at serious levels, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Nine cities, including Beijing, Shanghai, Xi'an and Tianjin,
reported slight air pollution, with Shanghai reporting high
nitrogen oxide levels and other cities reporting problems related
the the total volume of suspended particles.
</P>
<P>
Northwest China's Lanzhou, the only city recording medium air
pollution, reported a high volume of suspended particles during
the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
