<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni Determined to Fight Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has outlined several tendencies for corruption and reiterated the
government's determination to fight corruption.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement at a recent meeting with opinion leaders
at the State House, the Monitor paper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The president said corruption could be promoted by four
tendencies.
</P>
<P>
The first is that the head of state is corrupt himself; and
the second is when the president's subordinates are corrupt, he
is afraid of purging them.
</P>
<P>
The third is that the president may not be corrupt but his
investigators fail to perform their duties; and the last is that
the state attorneys make case files disappear so that the
magistrates and judges have to dismiss the cases due to lack of
solid evidence, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Investigation, prosecution and judgement are very vital
especially when you are following the law," Museveni said.
</P>
<P>
He holds that the easiest way to get rid of corruption is
political, calling on local leaders and members of parliament to
spearhead the anti-corruption crusade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
