<HEADLINE> Kaunda Ready to Meet Chiluba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Former Zambian President Kenneth
Kaunda has said he is ready to meet President Frederick Chiluba
to discuss matters of national development if he is invited.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview here Thursday Kaunda told Times of
Zambia that he has decided to quit party politics to concentrate
on matters affecting the country and he has always been willing
to meet Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
But he said his decision to quit party politics will not mean
that he will not criticize the government or his own party.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda has called for a central committee meeting of his
United National Independence Party (UNIP) to explain his reasons
for quitting party politics.
</P>
<P>
"I will criticize either UNIP or MMD (the ruling party) if
they do wrong things and I shall praise government when they do
something good," Kaunda said.
</P>
<P>
He dispelled fears that UNIP will fold up after his planned
retirement, saying UNIP is not KK (meaning Kaunda himself) and KK
is not UNIP and as such the party should continue with or without
him.
</P>
<P>
"This same KK will one day die. What will happen if i die? "
he asked.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was freed from under house arrest early last month
after the state entered a nolle prosequi.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was arrested on December 25 of 1997 but transferred to
under house arrest six days later following an international cry
for his immediate release or charging him.
</P>
<P>
On January 10, Kaunda was charged with conspiring with some
army officers to topple the government and one month later he was
formally charged with misprision of treason. 
</P>
