<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwestern Chinese Railway Helping The Economy There </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- After just over half a year, the
Nanning-Kunming Railway, which runs from the capital of the
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region to Yunnan Province via Guizhou
Province in southwestern China, has begun to have an effect on
local economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The 898-kilometer electrified railway line cost more than 10
billion yuan. It opened to traffic last November and has moved 3
million tons of cargo by now, including phosphorus from Yunnan,
coal from Guizhou, and aluminum from Guangxi.
</P>
<P>
The three areas still have more than 10 million poor people, or
approximately a quarter of China's total number, and the railway
was built with the intention of helping the needy.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou's nine counties and cities along the line have 12.1
billion tons of anthracite. The county of Xingren is expected
to produce a million tons of coal this year. Already it has helped
to bring a 47 percent increase in local revenues in the first four
months of this year, and the county's deputy magistrate, Zhou
Yuren, says that the railway has made it possible for the coal
industry to make a real economic contribution.
</P>
<P>
Convenient transportation has also encouraged local farmers to
grow more fruits and other cash crops. One prefecture of Guangxi,
for example, is estimated to produce 40 million kilograms of
mangoes this summer, a 25 percent increase over last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Amount of Drugs Burned in Changchun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Public Security Bureau in
Changchun, capital of northeast China's Jilin Province, recently
burned hundreds of kilograms of drugs in a public ceremony.
</P>
<P>
