<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood-Damaged Part of North-South Chinese Railway Resumes Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Nanchang section on China's
north-south railway trunk from Beijing to Kowloon in Hong Kong has
resumed operation after suspension for three days.
</P>
<P>
The bed of the railway sank and bent the tracks when it was
struck by flood waters on June 29, causing a 600-mm gap in the
railway track near the provincial capital city of Nanchang that a
train was using. But the cars were disconnected and four were
pulled to the North Nanchang Station and the others to the West
Nanchang Station and a serious accident that would be caused by
floods was avoided.
</P>
<P>
A engineering team of 950 people was rushed to scene and the
line to Beijing was able to reopen on the evening of June 30,
although speed was held to 5 kilometers per hour. The other track
opened to traffic the evening of July 2 and 20 passenger trains
that were stranded in water have all left for their respective
destinations.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the railway line between Yingtan city
in Jiangxi Province and the Xiamen Special Economic Zone in Fujian
reopened to traffic today after half a month of being closed as a
result of heavy flooding. And Cargo trains and some passenger
trains have resumed traffic.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
