<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Predicts Strong Growth for Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The African Development Bank (ADB)
has predicted that a strong and sustainable economic growth will
be realized by Nigeria, citing the country's rich resources and
efforts to diversify the economy.
</P>
<P>
The current efforts of Nigeria to develop agriculture and
natural gas are a testimony, the bank noted in its 1998 "African
Development Report", the Guardian reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The development of natural gas projects will gradually reduce
the economy's dependence on crude oil revenue," the bank report
said.
</P>
<P>
"The economy can also gain further strength with developments
in the agricultural sector, which has tremendous potentials for
productivity improvement," it added.
</P>
<P>
Given these, the ADB expects the real gross domestic product
(GDP) of Nigeria to grow by four to five percent in the medium
term.
</P>
<P>
The ADB report, however, does not give much hope on
manufacturing, saying that at least in the short term the
petroleum and agriculture sectors would continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
On conditions to realize the prediction, the report said, "the
growth outlook is contingent upon oil prices and favorable
climate conditions. Inflation is expected to continue the
declining trend over the forecast horizon, but market
intervention by the Central Bank is unlikely to prevent any
weakening of the Naira."
</P>
<P>
The bank projected Nigeria's inflation at 20 to 26 percent
range in the medium term, compared to its current single digit
level.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's real GDP grew at an average rate of five percent
during the 1987-1992 period, reflecting a slight improvement in
agriculture and manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, as oil price declined in 1993 amid political
uncertainties, the economy sank into a recession with real output
posting a mere 1.02 percent growth in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, real GDP growth rates have improved because of
higher oil prices. The regional apex multilateral institution
estimated Nigeria GDP growth rate for 1997 at 3.2 percent, which
is lower than the government figure of 3.77 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government has since 1994 been pursuing the goal
of macro-economic stability as a basis for accelerating the pace
of economic recovery and promoting sustainable growth.
</P>
<P>
In its current program of recovery, greater attention is paid
to trade liberalization, economic diversification and the
adoption of a relatively free foreign exchange system with guided
deregulation as a major policy framework. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
