<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Drafting Science Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- China expects to pass four laws on
various fields of science to encourage high-tech industrial
development and a national information program.
</P>
<P>
The Science and Technology Vice-minister Xu Guanhua told Xinhua
recently that the laws cover technology zones, high-tech
investment, science and technology funds, and scientific research
institutions.
</P>
<P>
Xu says that the Ministry will cooperate with the National
People's Congress' Education, Science, Culture, and Public Health
Committee in drafting the four laws, which are intended to
guarantee stable growth in science and technology.
</P>
<P>
China already has laws on science and technology development
and intellectual property rights protection, Xu explained, but
some need more detailed descriptions.
</P>
<P>
China has 53 state-level high-tech development zones employing
1.47 million people. They have a total industrial output worth 310
billion yuan (38.7 billion U.S. dollars) and exports of 5.5 billion
yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
