<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0730 GMT, July 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli soldiers and Palestinian policemen ended a
tense standoff in the Gaza Strip early Friday morning following
intensive mediation involving American and Egyptian officials,
Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
An agreement was reached to end the standoff after talks
between head of Israeli army's Southern Command Yom Tov Samiya and
Palestinian security chief in Gaza Mohammed Dahlan, the radio
said. (Israel-Palestinians-Standoff)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- More than 30 Pokot herdsmen living in western Kenya
have been killed in an ambush by Karamojong raiders from Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The attackers Thursday ambushed more than 200 Pokot youths who
were taking their animals for grazing at West Pokot's Lopitit
area, only five kilometers from the border, the Daily Nation
newspaper reported Friday. (Kenya-Border Raid)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ALMA-ATA -- The meeting of China, Kazakstan, Kyrgyzstan, Russia
and Tajikistan was held here at noon Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin, Kazak President Nursultan
A. Nazarbayev, Kyrgyz President Askar A. Akayev, Tajik President
Emomali S. Rakhmono, and Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov, who is entrusted as the special representative of
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, attended the meeting, which is
expected to focus on regional security and economic cooperation.
(Kazakstan-Five-Nation Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE --NATO's top official warned on Thursday that the
alliance would take steps to end the Kosovo conflict if a peaceful
solution was not found.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary General Javier Solana said in Sarajevo that NATO
backed a diplomatic end to the crisis, but was ready to take
further steps if necessary, the Yugoslav news agency Tanjug
reported. He hoped that talks on the Kosovo issue would continue,
but he warned that NATO would never allow another conflict like
the Bosnian war. (NATO-Solana-Kosovo) 
</P>
</TEXT>
