<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Private Sector Urged to Curb AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's National AIDS
Coordinating Program (NACP) has appealed to the private sector to
take a more active stance to the AIDS issue in the work place.
</P>
<P>
NACP Director Evaristo Marowa told a one-day seminar on
"company action on AIDS" here Thursday that although there had
been an increasing number of private concerns undertaking AIDS
interventions targeted at the work place, the response was
insufficient.
</P>
<P>
He said with the size of the problem, leadership and the
community did not seem to demonstrate the required urgency in
dealing with the issue.
</P>
<P>
According to UNAIDS, Zimbabwe and Botswana are leading the
world with one in every four adults estimated to be infected by
HIV, while nearly 15 years after the first AIDS case was
identified in Zimbabwe, an estimated 1.5 million people have
contracted HIV and more than 350,000 of these have developed full
blown AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"With so many people with HIV infection and affected by AIDS,
prevention interventions alone are not adequate. There is an
urgent need to strengthen focus on AIDS care, support and impact
alleviation strategies.
</P>
<P>
"AIDS has to be addressed with a clear understanding and
appreciation that it intermingles the issues of inequality,
poverty, culture and sexuality in complex ways," Marowa said.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the seminar noted that there was an urgent
need for clear government policy compelling the private sector to
establish a constructive policy for AIDS prevention program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
