<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Inflation Rate Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's inflation rate has risen
to 25.7 percent while the base lending interest rate in
commercial banks is also up, standing at 28.5 percent as the
country's economy continues to slide.
</P>
<P>
The fornight statistics of the central bank, the Bank of
Zambia shows that the degenerating macro-economic indicators have
been compounded by the continued reduction of gross international
reserves, which have dropped to 155 million U.S. Dollars from 255
million Dollars of last September.
</P>
<P>
No foreign exchange inflows have come to the central bank from
either the donor community or the Zambia Consolidated Copper
Mines (ZCCM) since Feburary, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The projected inflation rate of nine percent for this year has
suffered a setback with the high inflation rate of 25.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of the country's currency has continued to
be low with Kwacha at 1,952 against one Dolloar compared with
1,200 against one Dollar at the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Kwacha is likely to be devalued further as the lack of foreign
currency continues in the country.
</P>
<P>
Last week Germany said it will not release its aid to Zambia
as it pledged until ZCCM is privatized because the ZCCM is
losing.
</P>
<P>
In May this year the donors pledged to give Zambia an aid of
530 million Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
