<HEADLINE> Vice Premier Holds Talks with British Deputy Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier Wu Bangguo
held talks today with British Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott
and said the smooth handover of Hong Kong created favorable
conditions and a good atmosphere for the development of
Sino-British ties which have witnessed marked progress since the
British Labor Party took office.
</P>
<P>
Prescott serves concurrently as Secretary of State for the
Environment, Transport and Regions.
</P>
<P>
Wu told the British delegation that the joint efforts of the
two nations ensured the smooth transition and handover of Hong
Kong. "The two nations have witnessed increasing high-level
contacts this year," said Wu, adding that Chinese Premier Zhu
Rongji completed a highly successful visit to Britain and British
Prime Minister Tony Blair will visit China later this year.
</P>
<P>
"Increased contacts and consultations between leaders from the
two countries have added impetus to bilateral ties," said Wu.
</P>
<P>
He described Sino-British economic and trade links as generally
good. "Britain, China's second largest trade partner in Europe, is
continuing to increase investments in China," according to Wu.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that greater efforts can be made to explore more
channels and areas for cooperation and support enterprises,
particularly cooperation between small and medium-sized
enterprises in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Prescott said high-level exchanges have greatly promoted
bilateral cooperation and noted that Britain has cited 1998 as the
"Year of China." He noted that Britain is delighted at the fact
that closer cooperation in areas such as trade and culture will
further promote the development of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also exchanged views on furthering cooperation
in areas such as environmental protection and transportation.
</P>
<P>
Wu briefed members of the British delegation on China's
economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
