<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Province's Marine Police Emergency Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 3 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong Province
recently set up a marine police emergency network, according to
Lin Maoqing, deputy director of the Frontier Defence Bureau of
Guangdong, who said that the 50-million-yuan (6 million US
dollars) network includes both Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
All it takes is the touch of a button by any individual or ship
within range of the network and the Emergency Call Center
identifies the position of the individual or ship on its
electronic map instantly and responds, Lin explained.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that ultra-shortwave signals are a major
feature of the system and the province has 16 ultra-shortwave
automatic transfer stations on the mountains along Guangdong's
coast and the network can be used to deal with illegal activities
at sea as well as to help fishermen in trouble.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the center has received more than 1,200
emergency calls and had to respond in 130 situations, and help
pull 472 people out of danger.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
