<HEADLINE> Clinton on U.S.-Asia Relationship in Hong Kong (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. President Bill
Clinton stressed the importance of the relationship between the
U.S. and all of Asia here Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
He said: "We have a fundamental interest in promoting stability
and prosperity in Asia. Our future is tied to Asia's. A large and
growing percentage of our exports, our imports and our investments
involve Asian nations."
</P>
<P>
Addressing 900 business leaders at an event organized by the
Hong Kong Trade Development Council (TDC) and the American Chamber
of Commerce in Hong Kong, Clinton said that the recent events in
South Asia, in Indonesia, in financial markets all across the
region "remind the American people just how very closely our
future is tied to Asia's".
</P>
<P>
Noting a vast, rich, complex, dynamic relationship between the
U.S. and Asian nations built over the course of two centuries,
Clinton said: "at the dawn of the 21st century, our futures are
inextricably bound together -- bound by a mutual interest in
seeking to free future generations from the specter of war."
</P>
<P>
On the situation in Korean Peninsula, Clinton said: "We clearly
have an interest in trying to get a peace on the Korean Peninsula.
We will continue to work with China to advance our efforts in the
four-party talks, to encourage direct and open dialogue" between
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea and the Republic of
Korea.
</P>
<P>
"Our security is also enormously enhanced by a positive
partnership with a prosperous, stable, increasingly open China,
working with us, as we are, on the challenges of South Asian
nuclear issues, the financial crisis in the region, the Korean
peace effort, and others, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said: "our oldest ties to Asia are those of trade and
commerce, and now they've evolved into some of our strongest."
</P>
<P>
He said today roughly a third of U.S. exports and 4 million
jobs depend on its trade to Asia.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Hong Kong is now America's top consumer for cell
phones. Over 1,000 American companies have operations in Hong Kong
alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
