<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 06:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Troops End Standoff in Gaza </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli soldiers and Palestinian
policemen ended a tense standoff in the Gaza Strip early Friday
morning following intensive mediation involving American and
Egyptian officials, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
An agreement was reached to end the standoff after talks
between head of Israeli army's Southern Command Yom Tov Samiya and
Palestinian security chief in Gaza Mohammed Dahlan, the radio
said.
</P>
<P>
Dahlan persuaded Abdul Aziz Shahin, minister of supplies in the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) who led the Palestinians in
the standoff, to leave the restaurant where he was holding out.
</P>
<P>
To prevent possible armed conflict, Egyptian Ambassador to
Israel Mohammed Bassiouny and U.S. envoy Dennis Ross also
intervened late Thursday night by contacting Israeli Cabinet
Secretary Danny Naveh.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai also spoke by phone
with PNA deputy head Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen), as well as with
Ross, in a bid to resolve the dispute.
</P>
<P>
The tension began late Thursday when Palestinian police and
civilians blocked access to the Gush Katif Jewish settlement to
protest against Israeli closure of a section of a coastal road.
</P>
<P>
Israeli soldiers barred Shahin and a convoy of some 22
Palestinian vehicles from traveling from the Egyptian border to
Gaza City via the coastal road, part of which Israeli soldiers
said was off-limited to Palestinians for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
At the peak of the standoff, Israel sent reinforcements and
deployed tanks and armored personnel carriers at key points, while
Palestinian policemen took fortified positions a short distance
away. An Israeli army spokesman charged that this incident was
clearly a provocation planned by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said Israel and the PNA had agreed to set up a
joint committee to discuss the future of the disputed road. A
senior PNA official was quoted as saying that part of the road
would be open soon to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The standoff came at a time when tension is mounting between
the two sides due to the prolonged deadlock in the peace process,
which is stalled mainly by the dispute over Israeli second
pullback in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Adding to the tension, Israel and the PNA have beening trading
accusations over a recent Israeli decision to expand the
boundaries of the disputed holy city of Jerusalem and the PNA
efforts to upgrade its status in the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
