<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton on U.S.-Asia Relationship in Hong Kong (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to official sources, the U.S. is Hong Kong's second
largest trading partner and export market in 1997. Hong Kong's
two-way trade with the U.S. reached 442 billion HK dollars (57
billion U.S. dollars), up six percent from 1996. Hong Kong's total
export to the U.S. last year reached 316 billion HK dollars (44
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that in recent months when markets tremble in
Tokyo or Hong Kong they cause tremors around the world.
</P>
<P>
"That is why I have not only sought to ease the Asian economic
difficulties, but to institutionalize a regional economic
partnership through the Asian Pacific Economic Council leaders
meetings... That is why I'm also working to broaden and deepen our
economic partnership with China and China's integration into the
world economic framework," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to U.S.-China economic ties and trade, Clinton said
the United States purchases 30 percent of the exports of China --
far more than any other country in the world, far more than its
percentage of the world's GDP.
</P>
<P>
He stressed: "We very much want China to be a member of the
World Trade Organization."
</P>
<P>
"I also would say in that connection I am strongly supporting
the extension of normal trading status, or MFN to China," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Besides, he said that the United States and Asia are bound by
family ties, perhaps the most vital ones.
</P>
<P>
Clinton noted that seven million Americans today trace their
roots to Asia. Last year 3.4 million Americans traveled to Asia
and 7.8 million Asian traveled to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of young people are crossing the Pacific to study,
and in so doing, building friendships that will form the
foundations of cooperation and peace for the 21st century, he
said.
</P>
<P>
As the world becomes smaller, the ties between Asia and the
United States -- the political ties, the family ties, the trade
ties, the security ties -- they will only become stronger, he
said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of Commerce William Daley, TDC Chairman Dr.
Victor K. Fung and Chairman of the American Chamber of Commerce in
Hong Kong Jeffrey Muir also made speeches separately at the event.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton flew into Hong Kong from southwestern China's
picturesque city of Guilin Thursday evening on the last leg of his
nine-day China visit. He is scheduled to leave for home late
Friday evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
