<HEADLINE> Eastern Chinese Port Has Big Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The city of Zhoushan in China's
Zhejiang Province plans to build its port into a regional shipping
hub, mainly for transferring petroleum and minerals and for
transporting passengers.
</P>
<P>
It also expects to become an international transfer point,
trading place, and fishing base, Mayor Wang Huizhong told Xinhua
recently.
</P>
<P>
Zhoushan is a major part of the Shanghai International Shipping
Center and is playing an ever greater role in the province and the
country as a whole and is in urgent need of expansion, Wang says.
</P>
<P>
The city is on an archipelago and is looking for investment
from Chinese and overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the port handled more than 15 million tons of
goods. Over the past five years, Zhoushan has built or rebuilt
more than 30 docks, one of them a 250,000-ton crude oil dock and
an 80,000-ton refined oil products berth.
</P>
<P>
The mayor says that the port has excellent conditions for
further development and that large oil-carriers can move around
the area easily. 
</P>
</TEXT>
