<HEADLINE> Bulls Hope to Get Skiles for Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Chicago Bulls have showed
their interest to Phoenix Suns' assistant Scott Skiles and hoped
to hire him as the head coach for the six-time champion team,
according to a press report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The Bulls have asked the Suns permission to talk with Skiles
about replacing Phil Jackson. Skiles was among five or six
candidates for the Chicago job.
</P>
<P>
Skiles declined to comment on whether the Bulls or any other
team has contacted him or whether he expected to be a head coach
next season.
</P>
<P>
"This summer, next summer, I'm not tied up into a time or
anything," he said. "I'm just going through it like everyone else
does."
</P>
<P>
Suns general manager Bryan Colangelo said only that the club
told Skiles when he was hired that it wouldn't stand in the way of
his getting a head coaching job.
</P>
<P>
Skiles, 34, is considered one of the hot young coaching
prospects in the NBA. He played in the league for 10 years and
holds the NBA record with 30 assists in a game.
</P>
<P>
He first took coaching job in Greece, then joined the Suns last
year as coach Danny Ainge's top assistant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
