<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Mayor Calls for Establishing Satellite Towns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Satellite towns should be established
around Bangladesh's capital city of Dhaka to ease population
pressures on the city, English newspapers here reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"This is an urgency as the city's population will increase at
the beginning of next millennium, and by 2020 it will go beyond 20
million," Dhaka Mayor Mohammad Hanif said at a workshop on "Road
Safety Action Plan" jointly organized by the World Bank and the
Dhaka City Corporation here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Dhaka is now under an overload of 9 million people living in an
area of only 347 square kilometers against its capacity for 4
million to 5 million people, according to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
There is no dearth of law to check road accidents, but the
problem is the lack of effective enforcement, Hanif pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Accidents could be checked to some extent if licenses were not
issued to drivers of motorized and non-motorized vehicles before
testing their driving skills, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
A total of 90,000 licensed rickshaws presently ply the city
streets while the unofficial figure is estimated at more than
200,000, he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Dhaka alone had about 225,000 vehicles, more than half
of the country's total of about 425,000 at the end of 1997. The
actual number of vehicles plying the city can go up to about
300,000 because many vehicles enter from other parts of the
country every day, according to the Bangladesh Road Transport
Authority.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the mayor made an urgent call for building some
satellite towns around the city to mitigate the traffic and
population pressures on the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
