<HEADLINE> EU Commission, Austria to Work Together for Goal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The Austrian government set out its
priorities for the European Union rotating presidency on Thursday,
pledging to work with the European Commission, the executive body
of the Brussels-based EU.
</P>
<P>
The new partnership was stressed by Commission President
Jacques Santer and Austrian Federal Chancellor Viktor Klima after
their first working session in Vienna to coordinate their work.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders said the EU would focus on the expansion,
reforms and the fighting unemployment during Austria's EU
presidency over the next six months.
</P>
<P>
Santer said Austria would play a special and "center" role in
the eastward expansion because of its geographical position and
history.
</P>
<P>
But he said the problems with expansion, including financial
difficulties in admitting new member states, could not be solved
in one night.
</P>
<P>
Expansion would be extremely difficult without unanimity on the
issues, said Santer.
</P>
<P>
The commission president also agreed to speed up Agenda 2000,
which includes reforms in structure and agricultural policy. It is
obvious that the reforms would be Austria's main challenge.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian chancellor reaffirmed his goal of lowering
unemployment. He said that his country will continue to carry out
the policies of Britain, Austria's predecessor in the rotating EU
Presidency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
