<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Currency Devalued Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The taka, the currency of Bangladesh,
will be devalued by 1.7 percent from July 5, according to a
statement issued by the country's central bank, Bangladesh Bank,
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
This is the second devaluation of the taka so far in 1998 and
the 13th since the present government was formed in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The downward adjustment is in pursuance of the continuing
policy of maintaining incentives for exports and for inflow from
expatriate Bangladeshis, keeping in view the unfolding trends of
the currencies of trade partners and competitors of Bangladesh,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The bank's buying and selling rates for U.S. dollars with
authorized dealer banks shall respectively be 46.95 and 47.25 taka
per dollar effective from July 5, as against 46.15 taka for buying
and 46.45 taka for selling at present, the statement stated.
</P>
<P>
Exporters and the business community as a whole were asking the
government to devalue the national currency against the dollar,
which they said would accelerate exports, particularly ready-made
garments, press reports here said.
</P>
<P>
Though the devaluation might give an impetus to export to some
extent, it would likely to curb the country's imports, thus
further affecting country's revenue earnings, experts pointed out.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
