<HEADLINE> IMF Blamed for Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Thai Deputy Prime Minister Supachai
Panichpakdi has accused the International Monetary Fund (IMF) for
making wrong assessment of Thailand's crisis-hit economy.
</P>
<P>
The IMF did not heed Thailand's warnings last year that the
crisis threatened to turn into a regional financial maelstrom,
Supachai was quoted by Friday's The Nation newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
The IMF was wrong because it failed to predict that the crisis
would spread out to other countries in the region, Supachai said,
adding that Thailand had to warn the organization of a severe
economic recession.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks on the first anniversary of the baht
devaluation which triggered the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Thailand abandoned a 13-year peg of the baht against the dollar
and floated the currency on July 2 last year. The IMF came to
Thailand's rescue with a 17.2-billion-U.S.-dollar aid package soon
after the crisis broke out.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said the most serious problem facing the economy now
is a severe lack of liquidity in the private sector, resulting
from a tight monetary policy designed to prop up the battered
bath.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Thai share market rallied 5.1 percent in morning
trade yesterday in anticipation of new measures from Tokyo to
stimulate the ailing Japanese economy and repair its banking mess.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, IMF Managing Director Michel
Camdessus said in Frankfurt, Germany, on Thursday that Southeast
Asian nations had refused to listen to the fund's diagnosis and
advice given as long as 18 months before last year's financial
crisis broke out.
</P>
<P>
"Eighteen months before the eruption of the crisis which began
in July 1997, we visited the Asian countries a number of times.
But what can you do with governments that simply refuse your
diagnosis," Camdessus said at a symposium on the IMF's role,
according to reports reaching here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
