<HEADLINE> Big Savings Draw Air France to Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Air France announced on Friday the
relocation of its Asia-Pacific headquarters from Hong Kong to
Thailand as part of its strategy to cope with the economic
situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Marie-Joseph Male, director general of Air France in the
Asia-Pacific region, said in a press release that the move is in
line with the airline's policy of reducing expenses on facilities
and personnel.
</P>
<P>
"We can reduce our costs by 70 percent by relocating our
headquarters from Hong Kong to Thailand," Male said, adding that
the company could save up to 750,000 U.S. dollars a year by
utilizing Bangkok's cheaper facilities.
</P>
<P>
She said the cost savings of the move would be re-invested in
customer-oriented projects such as the re-launch of ground
services including reservation systems and ticketing across the
region.
</P>
