<HEADLINE> Indonesia Vows Not to Lease Out Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia would never need to lease
out its islands to overcome the current economic crisis if it
consistently implements its economic development programs, a
minister was quoted by Antara News Agency Friday as saying.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question, State Secretary/Minister Akbar
Tanjung told reporters here Thursday that his office had not put
forward a proposal to President B.J. Habibie concerning the
matter.
</P>
<P>
Issues on renting out Natuna islands in the South China Sea and
Biak district in Irian Jaya Province in the eastern part of the
country turned up when U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen
visited Indonesia a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
The United States left its naval base in the Subic Bay and its
airbase in Clark in the Philippines in 1991. It has been mooring
its ships in Singapore since then.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some people broached the idea of Indonesia
renting out Natuna and Biak to the United States for a military
base and using the money to bail Indonesia out of its economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Tanjung believed that Indonesia would successfully meet the
expectations expressed by the president at a meeting with top
Hindu priests recently.
</P>
<P>
Habibie told the Hindu priests that the economic condition of
the country would move toward a recovery late next year.
</P>
<P>
The main factor for economic recovery is that the political
condition in the country is conducive to the creation of
consistent measures by the government to overcome the ailing
economy, Tanjung added. 
</P>
