<HEADLINE> Thai Students Hit Hard as Crisis Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The economic crisis has taken its
toll on Thailand's human resource development as some 254,200
students nationwide had to end their studies due to its severe
effects on their family finances, according to the National
Education Council.
</P>
<P>
Of the number of students, 163,434 dropped out during the
school year and 90,780 did not turn up to further their study when
schools reopened, the council said in a report available Friday.
</P>
<P>
The highest rate of dropouts was reported at the primary
education level with a 119,631 dropouts nationwide, followed by
33,783 at the lower secondary and 10,020 at the upper secondary
level.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, private schools have been suffering from liquidity
problems due to delayed payments in tuition fees.
</P>
<P>
Some 307,845 students from all private-run schools have not yet
paid tuition fees to the schools, according to a survey by the
Office of the Private Education Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
