<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Finds Exercise Can Lower Cholesterol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- People with high cholesterol
need to exercise to get the full benefits of a healthy diet,
according to a study carried in Wednesday's Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
The study, by Marcia L. Stefanick of Stanford University,
looked at men and women who had moderately high LDL cholesterol
and low HDL, LDL increases the risk of heart attacks, while HDL
lowers it.
</P>
<P>
The 377 volunteers were already following healthy diets when
they were placed on the National Cholesterol Education Program's
Step Two diet, the stricter of its recommended low-fat diets.
Some were also assigned to an aerobics program.
</P>
<P>
One year later, they managed to cut their dietary fat intake by
about 8 percent. But without exercise, there was little change in
their LDL levels.
</P>
<P>
When exercise was added, the women's LDL fell by 15 percent and
the men's by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The program had no significant effect on their HDl levels nor
on their ratios of total to HDL cholesterol, which many experts
believe is an important measure of heart disease risk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Books in Chinese Libraries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Culture reports
that there are now 340 million books on the shelves of China's
public libraries, 3 million more than in 1996, or 126,000 books on
average for every library.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, that means a meager 0.31 for each person, and
most of those are in big city libraries.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 Chinese counties have no libraries of their own, and
it is still difficult for most people in poverty-stricken rural
areas to even find a book, Ministry officials say.
</P>
<P>
Libraries spent more money overall last year buying books, 30
percent more than in 1996 in fact, but, the problem of lack of
funds has not gone away.
</P>
<P>
Many libraries have to run cinemas, open restaurants, or sell
other goods just to support their basic business, Ministry
officials reveal, and say that, although there are more than 2,600
libraries in China, many of them occupy a very small space and
some don't even have reading rooms.
</P>
<P>
Officials are afraid that the situation will slow down China's
entry into the information age, in spite of the 7.1 billion books
published in this giant country last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
