<HEADLINE> Trade in Andean Countries Expected to Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Trade within the Andean Community
member countries is expected to amount to 6.8 billion U.S. dollars
this year, a growth of 23 percent over 1997.
</P>
<P>
Francisco Natera, chairman of Fedecamaras of Venezuela, was
quoted as saying by the local press Thursday that trade among
community countries reached 5.56 billion dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Jose Roig Justiniano, vice president of the Bolivian Foreign
Trade Institute, said that the products offered to Venezuela in
the agroindustrial sector included soy beans, soy meal, black and red
beans, fresh and dehydrated garlic, exotic flowers, palmetto buds
in brine, dehydrated llama meat and semifinished llama hides.
</P>
<P>
Bolivian demand for Venezuelan products included calcium
carbonate precipitate, wood furniture, fertilizer for hothouses,
and inputs for the plastics industry, said Roig.
</P>
<P>
The Bolivian National Statistics Institute said Bolivia
exported 239 million dollars worth of goods and services to the
Andean Community in 1997 and imported 160 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Andean Community, established in May 1969, comprises Peru,
Bolivia, Ecuador, Colombia, Venezuela and Panama. 
</P>
</TEXT>
