<HEADLINE> Tianjin Strives to Become Leading Economic Center in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, one of China's four
municipalities, plans to accelerate the reform of state-owned
enterprises and promote high-tech development over the next five
years in order to become a leading economic center in north China,
according to Mayor Li Shenglin.
</P>
<P>
The next five years will be crucial one for Tianjin's
development. The city, which has maintained an economic growth
rate higher than the national average, but is nonetheless
confronted with a number of grave challenges such as unemployment
and an irrational industrial structure, according to Li.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin will strive to raise its gross domestic product from
124 billion yuan in 1997 to 200 billion yuan by 2000, said Li.
</P>
<P>
The city, the largest industrial center in north China, is home
to 419 medium- to large-sized state-owned enterprises, half of
which are operating at a loss.
</P>
<P>
The city plans to help related enterprises turn losses into
profits by the year 2000, and will establish 10 enterprise groups
with annual sales volumes of 10 billion yuan each.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin will place priority on the development of electronic
information processing, bio-technology, new materials, new energy
and environmental technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
