<HEADLINE> Myanmar Seeks More Tourist Arrivals From Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is seeking more tourist
arrivals from Singapore to promote the country's tourism industry
by sponsoring a Myanmar Travel Show in Singapore due to begin
later Friday.
</P>
<P>
A 56-member Myanmar delegation comprising entrepreneurs from 34
hotels and tourism services will participate in the show and will
meet businessmen from airlines and travel agencies of Singapore to
seek cooperation opportunities with them especially in the air
transport services, the official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's investment in Myanmar ranked second after Britain
with more than 1.3 billion U.S. dollars in 65 projects at the end
of March, of which nine projects were in hotels and tourism,
according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Other hotel projects are mostly invested by Thailand, Japan,
Malaysia and China's Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
Since August last year, Singapore's Tourism Board, in
cooperation with the Myanmar tourism authorities, has been
conducting training courses in Yangon for Myanmar personnel in
hotel management under the two countries' economic and technical
cooperation agreement.
</P>
<P>
The two countries' air transport services, which help develop
tourism, have also been strengthened since both the Myanmar
Airways International, a Myanmar-Singapore joint venture, and the
Silk Air of Singapore are bringing in visitors directly from
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics, a total of 190,580 tourists from
24 countries and regions visited Myanmar in the 1997-98 fiscal
year, of whom Japan accounted for the largest number, followed by
Thailand, France and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
