<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Province Fighting to Save Oldest Giant Panda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Shasha, a female giant panda in the
Taiyuan Zoo in the capital of north China's Shanxi Province, is
recovering from a heart attack on the eve of her 33rd birthday.
</P>
<P>
Shasha is one of the few senior citizens among Chinese giant
pandas to live past 25. She stopped breathing suddenly on the
night of June 29, because of heart failure. Her heartbeat was
revived after emergency rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
Zoo keepers had been preparing for her birthday celebration and
ordered cake and candles. Local doctors and zoo keepers concluded
that Shasha is also suffering from epilepsy and cataracts because
of her age.
</P>
<P>
"It is very difficult to prolong a panda's life with current
medical measures because Shasha is too old and too sick," said
Bian Qizheng, a zoo doctor.
</P>
<P>
High temperatures, 37 degrees Celsius in Taiyuan on the night
when Shasha collapsed, is also hazardous to her health, Bian said.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda has not been able to eat or drink since she
fell ill, the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
"Shasha now relies on medicine and oxygen completely to extend
her life, and we will spare no efforts even if there is no
possibility for Shasha to survive," said Jia Zhongjian, director
of the zoo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
