<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Needs to Import More Rice: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines is expected to
import 2.2 million metric tons of rice in 1998 if the La Nina
weather phenomenon, which brings devastating rains and floods,
hits the country in July or August, a newspaper said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Secretary William Dar was quoted as saying earlier
that according to the country's meteorology agency, there is
already a 55-percent probability that La Nina, sister of El Nino,
will hit the country, up from the previous forecast of 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
The National Food Authority (NFA) has standby authority to
import 1.65 million metric tons of rice, of which around 1.2
million metric tons have already been brought in, the newspaper
The Philippine Star said.
</P>
<P>
But the food agency warned earlier that if La Nina comes in,
the country may need to import another 500,000 metric tons of
rice.
</P>
<P>
The final decision as to how much needs to be imported will be
handed down by the end of July.
</P>
<P>
The NFA has already started discussions with its traditional
rice suppliers, including Vietnam, Malaysia and Thailand, for
additional import volumes on top of the 1.65-million-metric-ton
standby. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
