<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Poor in Indonesia Reaches 79.4 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The number of poor people in
Indonesian has increased from 22.5 million in 1996 to 79.4 million
now due to the monetary crisis hitting the country since July
1997, according to the Central Bureau of Statistics (BPS).
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 22.6 million were living in urban areas and 56.8
million in villages in June, the local press quoted BPS Friday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The figures would increase to 95.8 million, or about 48 percent
of the total population of 202 million by the end of this year
because no economic recovery is in sight, BPS chief Suwito Sugito
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the bureau, a household is defined as poor if its
monthly earnings fall below 227,720 rupiah (15 U.S. dollars) in
urban areas and 177,997 rupiah (12 dollars) in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Sugito explained that the most recent estimates of numbers of
people living in poverty were not based on the biennial national
census survey, which is due next year, but on macroeconomic
indicators including the inflation rate, contraction in income,
changing consumption patterns, population growth and saving rates.
</P>
<P>
The country's per-capita income would fall as the result of a
forecast 10-percent contraction in the economy, he said, adding
that purchasing power would also be weakened by the expected
inflation rate of 80 percent. Inflation was running at 46.6
percent in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that a return to political stability is crucial if
the country is to recover from the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
In a recent agreement with the International Monetary Fund
provisions were made for the Indonesian government to begin a
social safety net program to help the poor survive the economic
crisis. Total funds channeled into this initiative are expected to
reach 7.5 percent of gross domestic product. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anhui Opens Wildlife Rescue Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, July 3 (Xinhua) -- East China's Anhui Province has
officially opened its wildlife rescue center.
</P>
<P>
The Wannan Wildlife Rescue Center, located at the outskirts of
Xiuning County, has an area of 16 hectares. The first phase
construction, at a cost of 4.3 million yuan, has ended while the
second phase should be completed in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The center will be turned into an education and training center
for the protection of wildlife by the end of this century, a
center official said.
</P>
<P>
So far the center has rescued more than 60 heads of wounded or
confiscated wild animals, and raised more than 30 types of rare
animals such as panthers, sikas, rhesus monkeys, peacocks and
swans.
</P>
<P>
After completion of the second construction phase, the center
will build three breeding bases, one specimen hall, one hall of
amphibious animals, and one veterinary station, the official
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
