<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Allows Direct Overseas Recruitment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government now
allows foreign employers to directly recruit the country's workers
to resolve the explosive unemployment problem, the local press
Friday quoted a government official as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We must seek as many job opportunities overseas as possible
for the jobless. About 15.4 million people have lost their jobs
and this figure is expected to continue rising in coming months,"
Minister of Manpower Fahmi Idris told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The government would simplify the official procedures to get
work documents while foreign employers have to be given access to
villages across the country to recruit workers, he said.
</P>
<P>
The new policy is aimed at easing the unemployment problem that
has been intensifying since the country sank into a crippling
economic crisis last year.
</P>
<P>
More and more companies are going bankrupt as the rupiah, the
country's currency, has lost about 80 percent of its value against
the U.S. dollar, while business has practically come to a halt
since the massive mid-May riots in Jakarta and other areas.
</P>
<P>
This new policy is also expected to help prevent workers from
taking the illegal way to go and work overseas, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that many job seekers leave Indonesia
illegally, mostly because of complicated bureaucratic procedures.
Besides, they have no money to pay the recruitment fee and are
extorted by unauthorized labor brokers and corrupt government
officials.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said the government is making efforts to
provide the maximum legal protection to workers abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Real Estate Sector Heats up in Fujian Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Real estate development has heated
up in east China's Fujian Province this year.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's investment in real-estate development increased by 3.1
billion yuan in the first five months of this year, or 9.1 percent
more than during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Official figures also indicate that Fujian's real-estate
developers sold commercial housing and office buildings with a
combined floor space of 780,000 square meters through May, a surge
of 98 percent year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
Currently, commercial buildings with a floor space of 13
million square meters are being constructed in Fujian, up 43.6
percent over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
In another analysis, some 600,000 square meters of area was
developed in the first five months, 19.7 percent more than the
comparable period last year.
</P>
<P>
However, a local official pointed out that greater efforts
should be made to market idle buildings, which have a combined
area of 3.39 million square meters.
</P>
<P>
While optimistic about the prospects of Fujian's real-estate
industry, developers must keep sober-minded and conduct good
market surveys to avoid blind investment, the official warned.
</P>
</TEXT>
