<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Tax revenue in June amounted to 4.9 billion
U.S. dollars, the second biggest figure in the economic history of
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The Economy Ministry attributed the rise to 300 million dollars
additional obtained in profits and another 60 million dollars from
personal assets.
</P>
<P>
Added value tax produced 1.89 billion dollars in June, a 12.8
percent increase.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The index of consumer prices in June was 0.95
percent, against 0.57 percent registered in May, the highest since
January.
</P>
<P>
Accumulated inflation for the first six months of the year was
4.57 percent.
</P>
<P>
The inflation index for the past 12 months reached 10.2
percent, higher than the single-figure target established by the
government for this year.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Mexico, Belize, Panama and the Central American
countries will hold an entrepreneurial forum on July 16 in El
Salvador, in an effort to integrate and exploit the advantages of
each nation.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the sectors of commerce, manufacturing,
services and the food industry will attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil will export 60,000 tons of pork to Russia in
the next five years in accordance with the agreements signed by
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The states of Santa Catarina and Rio Granden Do Sul in the
south of Brazil, the main producers of pork, were declared zones
free of foot and mouth disease at the beginning of this year by
the International Epizootic Organization.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The liquid flow of U.S. dollars from Brazil in June
amounted to 839 million, 495 million dollars less than in May.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Central Bank data registered an inflow of 1.26
billion dollars in June in the form of free rates, which operates
with dollars for foreign trade and in direct investments, stocks
and funds.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Japanese Bank of Exports and Imports
(Eximbank) granted Petroleos Mexicanos a one billion dollar credit
to finance the modernization and expansion of the productive
capacity of the Cantarell Complex.
</P>
<P>
Petroleos Mexicanos (Pemex) said that this credit was the most
important individual credit granted to the enterprise by a single
bank in the history of the oil firm.  
</P>
</TEXT>
