<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paper Boxes Oust Plastic on Railways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Nearly one month after plastic food
containers were banned on some trains, the railway authority is
still battling with the problem of finding a substitute of the
right quality.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Railways' Epidemic Prevention Division issued a
notice banning the use of plastic containers on through passenger
trains to Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou, to mark the 26th World
Environment Day, which fell on June 5.
</P>
<P>
The decision involves about 400 trains.
</P>
<P>
Ding Qinxue, head of the ministry, said one problem is that
liquid leaks from the paper boxes currently used as a substitute
for plastic containers.
</P>
<P>
Another problem is the relatively high price of paper boxes
compared with plastic ones.
</P>
<P>
Barring these inconveniences, paper boxes appear to perform
well, since they decompose rapidly in rainy seasons, he added.
</P>
<P>
Where they remain intact, rubbish collectors prefer to pick up
paper boxes, which have a higher recycling value. Plastic boxes
are generally left behind.
</P>
<P>
Ding stressed that substituting paper boxes is only an
experimental temporary solution.
</P>
<P>
"It is well known that paper making itself is one of the most
polluting industries," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Foreign Debt Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' outstanding foreign
debts rose to 51.1 billion U.S. dollars as of the first quarter of
the year from the year-ago level of 45.7 billion dollars,
according to the Central Bank of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
In a report published Friday, the central bank said that of the
total, those approved by or registered with the bank stood at 45.7
billion dollars, slightly higher than the 45.4 billion dollars as
of end-1997.
</P>
<P>
The figure included debts of the government, state
corporations, and private companies.
</P>
<P>
The central bank excluded from its computation a total of 5.4
billion dollars in private-sector loans which didn't get its
approval but were merely monitored.
</P>
<P>
These comprised 2.4 billion dollars of unregistered loans and
lease agreements of the private sector and 2.95 billion dollars
worth of inter-company accounts of foreign bank branches in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) earlier urged the central
bank to include these items in the computation as they tend to
understate the country's overall debt exposure.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said the rising debt was tempered by the
fluctuations in the exchange rate of various currencies against
the U.S. dollar, primarily the Japanese yen which fell to 131.9 at
the close of March from 130.4 by end-1997.
</P>
<P>
The debt level is expected to further rise as the new
administration expects to rely more on foreign borrowings to cover
a projected 40-billion-peso (1 billion dollars) budget deficit
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
