<HEADLINE> Defending Champ Hingis out of Wimbledon Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Martina Hingis of
Switzerland was knocked out of the Wimbledon Tennis Championships
Thursday after losing in straight sets to Czech tennis veteran
Jana Novotona.
</P>
<P>
Hingis, the reigning world tennis teenage queen, seemed to be
cruising to another easy victory after breaking Novotna's first
service. However, the 29-year-old Novotna displayed aggressive
tennis and effectively put Hingis on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
After snatching the first set 6-4, Novotna consolidated her
position and finally forced the world number one player out of the
championships by winning the second set by the identical score.
</P>
<P>
In the other women's semi-final confrontation, 30-year-old
Nathalie Tauziat of France booked her first grand slam final
position after beating her Belarussian opponent Natasha Zvereva by
1-6, 7-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
In the men's semi-final clashes to be staged Friday, defending
champion Pete Sampras of the United States will play 12-seed Tim
Henmen of Britain in order to defend his Wimbledon honor.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 1996 Wimbledon champion Richard Krajicek and
Croatian tennis ace Goran Ivanisevic will fight for the other
men's final spot. 
</P>
