<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Celadon Discovery Suggests Ancient Export Seaport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The discovery of more than a
thousand pieces of celadon dating to the Tang Dynasty (618-907)
provides further evidence that Ningbo in east China's Zhejiang
province has long served as a major export seaport.
</P>
<P>
The relics, including fragments of bowls, jars, dishes, plates,
boxes, and kettles, were mainly produced by a famous Tang Dynasty
kiln famous for its celadon and Mise, or strangely colored
porcelain.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts note that the find verifies records that Ningbo
was one of three major Tang Dynasty export seaports along with
Yangzhou in east China's Jiangsu Province and Guangzhou in south
China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Porcelain produced by different kilns during the Song Dynasty
(960-1279) have also been found in the upper layer at the site.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists have also unearthed remnants of a moat built
during the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Censures U.S. Dairy Export Incentive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wellington, July 3 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand, one of the world's
major dairy product exporters, Friday protested against U.S.
subsidization of its dairy exports through its Dairy Export
Incentive Program (DEIP).
</P>
<P>
New Zealand's protest followed this week's announcement by the
United States of the 1998/1999 round of DEIP subsidies, which are
applied to designated quantities of products and assist the
competitiveness of U.S. dairy exports in international markets.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that in 1998/1999, the United States will
subsidize 84,212 tons of skimmed milk powder exports (compared
with a subsidy allocation of 92,217 tons in 1997/1998), 29,854
tons of butterfat (34,232 tons in 1997/1998), 5,003 tons of whole
milk powder (7,487 tons in 1997/1998), and 3,350 tons of cheese
(3,510 tons in 1997/1998).
</P>
<P>
"While we note that the United States has reduced its DEIP
subsidies as required under its Uruguay Round obligations, we will
continue to advocate the elimination and prohibition of this and
all forms of export subsidies," New Zealand Minister of
Agriculture Lockwood Smith said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
He urged the United States to end these DEIP subsidies "as soon
as possible."
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand minister said his country would monitor closely
the practical impact of the latest subsidy allocations on world
prices and on New Zealand's unsubsidized dairy exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980703.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman: "Three Noes" on Taiwan is U.S. Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Spokesman for the U.S. State
Department James Rubin said here Thursday that the "three noes" on
Taiwan is the U.S. policy stated on several occasions.
</P>
<P>
At a routine daily press briefing, Rubin said: "The fact that
we have a position on not supporting Taiwan independence; not
supporting one China, one Taiwan; not supporting Taiwan membership
in international organizations that require the party to be a
state is something I've said from this podium. In fact, I
remember saying it."
</P>
<P>
Rubin was the first U.S. official who explicitly announced the
"three noes" on Taiwan last October when Chinese President Jiang
Zemin visited Washington.
</P>
<P>
The issue of Taiwan has been at the core of Sino-U.S.
relations. China demands the United States stick to the three
joint communiques signed with China and stop arms sales to
Taiwan. Committing itself to the "one China" policy embodied in
the three joint communiques, Washington says that it is also bound
by the "Taiwan Relations Act" enacted by Congress.
</P>
<P>
The law authorizes U.S. arms sales to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The sale of a large number of F-16 jet fighters to Taiwan in
the 1990s and the open attempts on the part of Taiwan to seek
independence have prompted China to urge the United States to be
less ambiguous about its Taiwan policy.
</P>
<P>
Rubin for the first time made the "three noes" clear and public
within the context that the United States and China are seeking
constructive strategic partnership toward the next century.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman recalled Thursday that this policy was reiterated
by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in May when she visited
Beijing to prepare the ground for President Bill Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton left Guilin in southern China Wednesday and
is now in Hong Kong, the last leg of his nine-day trip to China.
He is returning home Friday. He was the first U.S. president to
visit China in almost 10 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
