<HEADLINE> U.S. Orders Immediate Inspections on Newest 737 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government Thursday
ordered immediate inspections on engines on the newest Boeing 737s
following two inflight engine shutdowns caused by broken engine
parts last week.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Aviation Administration ordered immediate
inspections on 46 engines installed on 23 U.S. airliners, 13 of
which are owned by Southwest Airlines. Nine others are owned by
Continental Airlines and one is owned by Eastwind Airlines.
</P>
<P>
It also stated that the engine part in question, the accessory
gearbox starter gearshaft, must be replaced on all of the aircraft
by September 1 or within the next 750 flight hours.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, two incidents involved the latest versions of the
world's most common airliner, the Boeing 737-700 and -800
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The pilots for two jets flown by Russia's Transaero Airlines
and Norway's Braathens Airlines had to shut off one of their
aircraft's two engines after a gearshaft broke. 
</P>
</TEXT>
