<HEADLINE> Senate Democratic Leader Blasts Tobacco, Insurer Ad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Tobacco and health insurance
companies may have violated federal law with million-dollar
advertising blitzes and should be added to the Justice
Department's inquiry into campaign finance abuses, U.S. Senate
Democratic leader Tom Daschle said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"I fear that these practices will constitute a trend and result
in yet another loophole in our campaign finance laws," Daschle
said in a letter Thursday to Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
The senator said the investigation should be based in part on a
complaint against tobacco companies filed with the Federal
Election Commission Monday by the National Campaign for
Tobacco-Free Kids.
</P>
<P>
The anti-smoking group alleges that the industry will add to
its 40 million-dollar advertising campaign new ads endorsing
Republican senators who voted to kill the Senate's tobacco bill on
June 17.
</P>
<P>
Health insurance companies are preparing a similar campaign,
Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
Citing federal law that prohibits firms from contributing to
candidates, the complaint "makes a persuasive case that this next
phase of advertising is solely intended to affect the outcome of
federal elections, not public policy," Daschle said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco industry spokesman Scott Williams said this week that
the advertisements would comply with federal law.
</P>
<P>
Reno also should investigate the health insurance industry,
which "is now employing an identical advertising strategy in its
attempt to defeat federal reforms of managed care practices and
health maintenance organizations," according to Daschle.
</P>
<P>
"We see this as an attempt to silence our ads and to gag us,"
responded Susan Pisano, spokeswoman for the American Association
of Health Plans. "Our ads are focused squarely on the issue of
government mandates, both state and federal, and not even on any
specific piece of legislation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
