<HEADLINE> World Bank Provides 1 Bln Dlr Loan to Support Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank Thursday approved
a 1 billion U.S. dollar loan to support policy reforms in the
trouble-ridden Indonesia as a key step towards economic revival.
</P>
<P>
The latest policy reform initiative supports a program jointly
developed by the Indonesian government, the International Monetary
Fund, the Asian Development Bank and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
It aims at achieving a restoration of confidence and growth,
protection of the poor from the worst effects of the financial
crisis and particularly punishing drought, as well as smoother
transition of consumption and investment levels and stronger
management and protection of the country's environment.
</P>
<P>
Of the new loan, 600 million dollars will be disbursed
immediately with the balance due for delivery later this year,
following approval in recent months of nearly 400 million dollars
in World Bank project loans designed to improve rural development,
education and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has pledged a total of 4.5 billion dollars to
Indonesia over three years in response to the financial crisis and
the country's development needs. Of this total, the bank is
expected to contribute 2 billion dollars to assist economic
reforms, including money for humanitarian needs, while the
remaining 2.5 billion dollars will fund project loans that stress
poverty alleviation and social investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
