<HEADLINE> U.S Doubtful of Pakistani Defector's Nuclear Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States Thursday cast
doubt on the claim by a Pakistani defector that Islamabad had
planned a preemptive strike on Indian nuclear facilities.
</P>
<P>
"We have no information to support this person's claim that
Pakistan was planning a preemptive strike on Indian nuclear
facilities," State Department spokesman James Rubin told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"And we note significant discrepancies in his story, as
reported in the press," he added.
</P>
<P>
Iftikhar Khan Chaudry, seeking asylum in the United States as a
defector from Pakistan's nuclear weapons program, said Wednesday
at a new conference in New York that Pakistan had planned a
preemptive nuclear attack on India on April 25. He and other
researchers who opposed the strike threatened to expose it
publicly, he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan
said Chaudry was an impostor who exposed the U.S. authorities as
simpletons.
</P>
<P>
Khan also vigorously denied that Pakistan had or would ever
plan such preemptive attack on India.
</P>
<P>
"The truth is that there was (not) and never has been any plan
in Pakistan for preemptive or nuclear strikes against India. We
certainly have been saying that if India attacks we will
retaliate," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chaudry fled Pakistan and entered the United States from
Canada on May 22 seeking political asylum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
