<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibian Scientists Find Ancient Skull Fossil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 2 (Xinhua) -- Two paleontologists have
found a skull in Namibia which they believe may prove to be the
missing link between modern man and his ancestor, homo erectus or
the axe man.
</P>
<P>
Martin Pickford and Brigitte Senut told reporters on Thursday
that the skull is believed to be about 100,000 years old, placing
it in the Middle Stone Age, and possesses features of the axe man
and of early humans.
</P>
<P>
The skull, which was found at the mouth of the Orange River in
Namibia, also has the distinction of being the oldest human
fossil skull found in that country, South African Press
Association said.
</P>
<P>
Mine manager Daan Marais found the skull lying in a sandbar at
the mouth of the river about 10 years ago and took it home. It
was only years later that he mentioned the skull to the two
paleontologists who are part of a Franco-Namibian paleontology
expedition.
</P>
<P>
When Pickford and Senut saw the skull, they immediately
identified it as being a very ancient human being.
</P>
<P>
"Finding the link to modern man and homo erectus has never
been properly investigated because more emphasis was placed on
finding older fossils.
</P>
<P>
"We were just lucky to have stumbled onto this skull. There
are paleontologists who have been working in areas for years
looking for fossil evidence of a link."
</P>
<P>
He said that the finding places Namibia firmly on the
paleoanthropological map.
</P>
<P>
The well fossilized specimen, nicknamed Old Man River after
its place of origin, consists of a top cranial section which
stops just above the eyes and the back section of the skull.
</P>
<P>
Senut said the skull possesses indentations from veins, which
makes it possible to see which area of the brain was receiving
the most blood.
</P>
<P>
"The skull is larger than homo erectus, but is larger at the
back and tapers towards the front which is different to modern
man," she said. "The veins also show the back lobes of the brain
getting more blood than the front."
</P>
<P>
The frontal lobes are considered areas for thought
development.
</P>
<P>
"Its distinguishing features include thick eyebrow ridges, a
low forehead and a thick skull, all of which suggest he was an
archaic homo sapiens," she said.
</P>
<P>
Senut said that it was difficult to date the specimen, which
had been washed down the river probably during a flood.
</P>
<P>
"Without its geographical context, it is difficult to say with
certainty how old the fossil is," she said.
</P>
<P>
Clay deposits containing hippopotamus and giraffe footprints
have been located at a site near to where the skull was found and
excavations are planned in the hope of finding stone tools and
other bones.
</P>
<P>
According to Senut, amateurs had found fossil hippopotamus
teeth at the site several years ago.
</P>
<P>
"These may yield some information about the age of the
deposits, which are believed to be about 100,000 years old on the
basis of comparisons with other archaic human fossils."
</P>
<P>
The two paleontologists have received permission from the
Namibian government to take the skull to France where tests will
be conducted to determine among other things the age and the sex
of the fossil.
</P>
<P>
"I am sure once we get the tests back on the fossil, it will
provoke a lot of debate," Pickford said. "We may not know for
sure if this is the missing link for another 10 years."
</P>
<P>
After being studied in France, Old Man River will be put on
display at a Namibian museum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
